46 additional coronavirus cases in South Carolina, statewide total rises to 173 |work=[[WBTV]] |language=en-US|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Governor McMaster and State Superintendent of Education Molly Spearman announce that public schools statewide, including colleges and universities, will remain closed through the end of April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golaurens.com/news/sc-schools-to-remain-closed-through-april/article_2deb289e-6e02-11ea-a60b-abceb632d77b.html|title=SC schools to remain closed through April|date=24 March 2020|website=GoLaurens.Com|language=en|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wyff4.com/article/south-carolina-schools-will-remain-closed-until-the-end-of-april-governor-says/31916572|title=South Carolina schools will remain closed until the end of April, governor says|date=24 March 2020|website=WYFF|language=en|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] adopted a stay-at-home ordinance effective March 26 for two weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charleston City Council approves 'stay at home' ordinance with broad exceptions for businesses|first1=Mikaela|last1=Porter|first2=Thad|last2=Moore|work=[[The Post and Courier]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/health/covid19/charleston-city-council-approves-stay-at-home-ordinance-with-broad/article_0a29c94e-6de7-11ea-84b1-c3369b331f03.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 29 for 14 days.<ref>{{cite news|title=Columbia adopts ordinance to stop spread of coronavirus|first=Stephen K.|last=Benjamin|authorlink=Stephen K. Benjamin|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.thestate.com/news/coronavirus/article241529271.html}}</ref> [[Williamsburg County, South Carolina|Williamsburg County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 27 for 14 days.<ref>{{cite news|title=County leaders issue 'stay at home' order for Williamsburg County|first=Ray|last=Rivera|publisher=[[WCSC-TV]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020|url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/03/27/officials-issue-stay-home-order-williamsburg-county/}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, [[Mount Pleasant, South Carolina|Mount Pleasant]] issued a stay-at-home order effective April 2 until April 15.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mount Pleasant issues 'Stay at Home' order, stops short-term rentals|publisher=[[WCIV]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://wpde.com/news/local/mount-pleasant-mayor-expected-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-tuesday}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, South Carolina governer Henry McMaster issued a statewide \"home or work\" order which goes into effect Tuesday at 5 p.m.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/public-global-health/491431-south-carolina-issues-home-or-work-order|title=South Carolina issues 'home or work' order|last=Coleman|first=Justine|date=2020-04-06|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Earlier in the day, [[Beaufort, South Carolina|Beaufort]] issued a shelter-in-place order effective until April 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=City of Beaufort leaders pass 'shelter-in-place' order|publisher=[[WCSC-TV]]|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020|url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/04/06/city-beaufort-leaders-pass-shelter-in-place-order/}}</ref>\n\n==South Dakota==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Dakota}}\nMarch 13, Governor Noem declared a state of emergency; Schools are closed beginning March 16.<ref>[https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/friday-covid-19-south-dakota-update-1-more-positive-case/ Noem signs State of Emergency order; Requests schools to close throughout South Dakota next week] [[KELO-TV|KELO]]</ref><ref>[https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/state-and-regional/noem-orders-south-dakota-k--schools-to-close-next/article_14ddb2a4-3a5d-5a1c-b467-eb3327f2392e.html Noem orders South Dakota K-12 schools to close next week; Iowa, Nebraska holding off on similar moves] Sioux City Journal</ref>\n\n== Tennessee ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee#Government response}}\nOn March 15, the mayor of [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] imposed restrictions on restaurants and closed bars in [[Davidson County, Tennessee|Davidson County]].<ref name=\":12a\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2020/03/15/coronavirus-tennessee-latest-news-virus-national-emergency/5052035002/ |title=Coronavirus in Tennessee latest news: Restaurant restrictions, ACMs delayed and 39 confirmed cases in Tennessee |website=The Tennessean |language=en |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 19, the mayor of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]] issued an executive order closings gyms and prohibiting dine-in service for restaurants and bars indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newschannel9.com/news/local/mayor-berke-to-announce-executive-order-thursday-that-suspends-dine-in-restaurant-service|title=Update: More local communities pass new COVID-19 restrictions|website=News Channel 9|language=en|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the mayor of [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] issued an executive order closing bars, gyms, and commercial event venues and restricting restaurants to delivery and take-out service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wate.com/health/coronavirus/knoxville-mayor-kincannon-issues-executive-order-closing-bars-gyms-clubs-puts-limits-on-restaurants/|title=Knoxville Mayor Kincannon issues executive order closing bars, gyms, clubs; puts limits on restaurants|website=WATE|language=en|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Nashville's Metro Public Health Department issued a stay-at-home order effective for at least 14 days for Nashville and Davidson County.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cooper Issues Stay-at-Home Order |first=Kara |last=Hartnett |work=[[Nashville Scene]] |date=March 22, 2020 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://www.nashvillescene.com/news/pith-in-the-wind/article/21123674/cooper-issues-stayathome-order}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Safer At Home Order|work=Nashville COVID-19 Response|publisher=Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.asafenashville.org/safer-at-home-order/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Knoxville and [[Knox County, Tennessee|Knox County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective for at least 14 days beginning March 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wate.com/news/knox-county-closes-all-nonessential-businesses-with-safer-at-home-order/|title=Knox County closes all nonessential businesses with \u2018safer at home order\u2019|website=WATE|language=en|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] issued a \"safer-at-home order\" effective through April 7, and surrounding [[Shelby County, Tennessee|Shelby County]] and the county's other municipalities issued a similar order the same day.<ref>{{cite web|title=COVID-19 Update from Mayor Strickland|publisher=City of Memphis|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url=https://covid19.memphistn.gov/covid-19-update-from-mayor-strickland-3-23/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Shelby County Mayor, suburban cities under Stay At Home order|first1=Mitchell|last1=Koch|first2=Jone\u00e9|last2=Lewis|work=[[WREG-TV]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url=https://wreg.com/news/live-shelby-county-health-department-updates-on-coronavirus/}}</ref> \n\nOn March 24, [[Franklin, Tennessee|Franklin]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 25 for seven days.<ref>{{cite news|title=City of Franklin issues 'Stay at Home Order'|publisher=[[WSMV-TV]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.wsmv.com/news/city-of-franklin-issues-stay-at-home-order/article_d4d8bc28-6dfa-11ea-8346-8f1cd038181b.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Governor [[Bill Lee (Tennessee politician)|Bill Lee]] issued a two-week safer at home order for the entire state, which covers the closure of all nonessential businesses and will go into effect at 11:59&nbsp;p.m. the following day. The order will last until April 14.<ref>{{cite news|last1= Kelman|first1=Brett|last2=Allison|first2=Natalie|title= Tennessee Gov. Bill Lee issues two-week 'safer at home' order, closes non-essential businesses|url= https://amp.tennessean.com/amp/2937429001|accessdate=March 30, 2020|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, [[Clarksville, Tennessee|Clarksville]] and surrounding [[Montgomery County, Tennessee|Montgomery County]] issued shelter-in-place orders effective April 1 until April 8.<ref>{{cite news|title=Clarksville, Montgomery County issue their own 'shelter-in-place' orders|first=Stephanie|last=Langston|publisher=[[WKRN-TV]]|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.wkrn.com/community/health/coronavirus/clarksville-montgomery-county-issue-their-own-shelter-at-home-orders/}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, Governor Lee issued a statewide stay-at-home order effective through April 14.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tennessee governor issues stay-at-home order|first=Robert|last=Sorrell|work=[[Bristol Herald Courier]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|url=https://www.heraldcourier.com/news/tennessee-governor-issues-stay-at-home-order/article_4c294446-7517-11ea-a70a-e7ce87cd1a7a.html}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, Chattanooga issued a shelter-in-place order.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chattanooga Mayor Andy Berke issues 'Shelter in Place' order for city, closing non-essential businesses|publisher=[[WRCB]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|url=https://www.wrcbtv.com/story/41966936/chattanooga-mayor-andy-berke-issues-shelter-in-place-order-for-city-closing-nonessential-businesses}}</ref>\n\n==Texas==\n{{main||2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas#Government response}}On March 2, San Antonio Mayor [[Ron Nirenberg]] and [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]] both declared a \"local state of disaster and a public health emergency\" after an individual was mistakenly released from quarantine at Joint Base San Antonio by the CDC before a third test for coronavirus returned a positive result.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kens5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bexar-county-coronavirus-public-health-emergency/273-788a002b-1b08-49d0-9a27-da639e6fed47 |title=Bexar County joins San Antonio in declaring public health emergency over coronavirus |last=Floyd |first=Jackson |date=March 2, 2020 |work=[[KENS]]|url-status=live|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, the city and county issued a shelter-in-place order effective March 24 through April 9.<ref>{{cite news|title=San Antonio and Bexar County Impose Shelter-in-Place Order Through April 9 to Contain Coronavirus Spread|first=Sanford|last=Nowlin|work=[[San Antonio Current]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url=https://www.sacurrent.com/the-daily/archives/2020/03/23/san-antonio-and-bexar-county-impose-shelter-in-place-order-through-april-9-to-contain-coronavirus-spread}}</ref>\n[[File:Map of 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas latest.svg|thumb|Counties in Texas with confirmed COVID-19 cases]]\nOn March 13, Texas Governor [[Greg Abbott]] declared a statewide disaster for all [[List of counties in Texas|counties in the state]]. Abbott also announced the first drive-through testing facility in San Antonio, and will expand to other cities across the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/13/texas-coronavirus-cases-state-emergency-greg-abbott/ |title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott issues disaster declaration over coronavirus |date=March 13, 2020|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/texas/article/Dallas-bans-large-gatherings-amid-c