, 2020|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/local/more-shelter-place-orders-pop-around-metro-atlanta/NqZDVMvXZwKeWvjE98mo6M/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, [[Clayton County, Georgia|Clayton County]] issued a shelter-in-place order for unincorporated parts of the county effective April 1 through April 12 at the earliest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Unincorporated Clayton County under COVID-19 shelter in place order as of 12:01 a.m. Tuesday, April 1|first=Robin|last=Kemp|work=[[Clayton News Daily]]|location=Jonesboro, Georgia|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|url=https://www.news-daily.com/news/unincorporated-clayton-county-under-covid-19-shelter-in-place-order-as-of-12-01-a/article_99efbfe2-73a1-11ea-98de-4b554a731b6a.html}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] issued a stay-at-home order.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fulton County issues shelter in place order; violators could get $1,000 fine or up to year in jail|first=Jonathan|last=Raymond|publisher=[[WXIA-TV]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://www.11alive.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/fulton-county-coronavirus-shelter-in-place-order/85-f7eb2956-6447-43ce-adb1-4268a8c2fcfc}}</ref> [[Dahlonega, Georgia|Dahlonega]] issued a stay-at-home order effective April 3 through April 17.<ref>{{cite news|title=City issues stay-at-home order, tightens restrictions|first=Greg Jr.|last=Finan|work=[[The Dahlonega Nugget]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://www.thedahloneganugget.com/news/city-issues-stay-home-order-tightens-restrictions}}</ref> Governor [[Brian Kemp]] announced that he will issue a statewide shelter-in-place order on April 2, to be effective April 3 through 13.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gov. Kemp to issue statewide shelter-in-place order, close schools through current year|first=John|last=Ruch|work=Reporter Newspapers|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://www.reporternewspapers.net/2020/04/01/gov-kemp-to-issue-statewide-shelter-in-place-order-close-schools-through-current-year/}}</ref>\n\n==Hawaii==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Hawaii}}\nOn March 4, Governor David Ige declared a state of emergency until April 29.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 4, 2020|access-date=March 5, 2020 |title=Gov. David Ige issues emergency proclamation in response to coronavirus |work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]] |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/04/breaking-news/watch-live-gov-david-ige-and-hawaii-health-officials-give-update-on-coronavirus-in-hawaii/|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 21, Ige ordered a 14-day mandatory quarantine for travelers.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/21/breaking-news/watch-live-gov-david-ige-provides-update-on-coronavirus-in-hawaii/ |title = VIDEO: Gov. David Ige mandates 14-day quarantine for visitors to Hawaii, returning residents|date = March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, [[Honolulu County, Hawaii|Honolulu County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective until April 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=VIDEO: Honolulu Mayor Kirk Caldwell issues stay at home, work from home order|first=Timothy|last=Hurley|work=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/22/breaking-news/watch-live-honolulu-mayor-kirk-caldwell-discusses-coronavirus/}}</ref> [[Maui County, Hawaii|Maui County]] issued a similar order effective from March 25 to April 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maui 'stay at home and work from home' order starts Wednesday|first=Kehaulani|last=Cerizo|work=[[The Maui News]]|location=Wailuku, Hawaii|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2020/03/maui-stay-at-home-and-work-from-home-order-starts-wednesday/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor [[David Ige]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 25 through April 30.<ref>{{cite news|title=Governor orders statewide 'stay-at-home' order with potential criminal penalties|first=John|last=Burnett|work=[[Hawaii Tribune-Herald]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url=https://www.hawaiitribune-herald.com/2020/03/23/hawaii-news/governor-orders-statewide-stay-at-home-order-with-potential-criminal-penalties/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the Kauai Police Department began checkpoints to ensure compliance on the island. Residents were stopped in their vehicles and asked to provide reasons for travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2020/03/26/kauai-police-begin-islandwide-checkpoints-lockdown-compliance/|title=Checkpoints set up on Kauai, 2 arrests on Oahu as police enforce stay-at-home order|last=Staff|first=H. N. N.|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==Idaho==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Idaho#Government response}}\nOn March 13, Governor Brad Little announced a state of emergency on the state. The state of emergency triggers Idaho price gouging law that prohibits the sale of fuel, drugs, food, and water at excessive price during a state of emergency.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://idahonews.com/news/coronavirus/idahos-price-gouging-law-in-effect-after-state-of-emergency-declaration |title=Idaho's price gouging law in effect after state of emergency declaration |last=Morrison |first=Ryan L. |date=March 13, 2020 |website=KBOI|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, [[Blaine County, Idaho|Blaine County]] imposed a stay-at-home order effective until April 6.<ref name=\"Wired Martineau\">{{cite news |title=What's a 'Shelter in Place' Order, and Who's Affected? |first=Paris |last=Martineau |work=[[Wired News]] |date=March 22, 2020 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://www.wired.com/story/whats-shelter-place-order-whos-affected/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, the Idaho State Board of Education directed all public school districts to start a \u201csoft closure\u201d of all classroom facilities immediately, to continue through April 20.<ref name=\"IdahoSBOESchoolClosure\" />\n\nOn March 25, Idaho Governor [[Brad Little]] issued a stay-at-home order for the entire state, effective for 21 days.<ref>{{cite news|title=Idaho governor issues statewide stay-at-home order, signs 'extreme emergency declaration'|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 29, 2020|publisher=[[KTVB]]|url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/idaho-stay-at-home-order-shelter-coronavirus-governor-brad-little/277-3a69d247-036e-4535-9bff-4e5543768d95}}</ref> The order requires \"all persons living in the State of Idaho to self-isolate at their place of residence\" excepting leaving to obtain or provide essential services.<ref>[https://coronavirus.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/127/2020/03/statewide-stay-home-order_032520.pdf ]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>  The order also closes non-essential businesses and government operations.  Restaurants may remain in operation, but for carry-out service only.  The order also contains instructions for social distancing.  Little also signed an \"extreme emergency declaration\" which allows the state \"to more effectively increase health care capacity, take steps to reduce and slow coronavirus spread, and take rapid and decisive steps to improve the condition of Idahoans whose job and incomes are being harmed by the pandemic.\"<ref>{{cite press release|date=March 25, 2020|access-date=March 29, 2020|title=Governor Little issues statewide stay-home order, signs extreme emergency declaration|url=https://gov.idaho.gov/pressrelease/governor-little-issues-statewide-stay-home-order-signs-extreme-emergency-declaration/}}</ref>\n\n==Illinois==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Illinois#Government response}}\n\n[[File:The Bean.jpg|thumb|right|[[The Bean]] in [[Chicago]] cordoned off on March 22, 2020]]\n\nJacqueline B. Vaughn Occupational High School, which serves students with special needs in Chicago, was closed from March 7 to 19. All schools in Illinois will be closed for two weeks starting March 17.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2020/03/15/coronavirus-school-closings-closures-kids-quarantine-symptoms-special-needs-illinois/5034633002/ Coronavirus closed this school. The kids have special needs: 'You can't Netflix them all day.'] by Erin Richards, USA Today, March 15, 2020</ref> All Chicago public schools will be provided with free meal pickup from Monday through Friday.<ref>[https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/all-chicago-public-schools-to-offer-free-meal-pickup-during-coronavirus-closure/2237714/ All Chicago Public Schools to Offer Free Meal Pickup During Coronavirus Closure] NBC 5 Chicago, March 15, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Chicago Mayor [[Lori Lightfoot]] canceled Chicago's two [[St. Patrick's Day]] parades.<ref>[https://www.chicagotribune.com/coronavirus/ct-chicago-st-patricks-day-parade-cancelled-coronavirus-20200311-d5gtbxofc5hxpdfocdepwfsxca-story.html Chicago Mayor Lori Lightfoot cancels St. Patrick's Day parades because of coronavirus, says they'll be rescheduled] by John Byrne, Chicago Tribune, March 11, 2020</ref>\n\nChicago businesses report a slowdown amid fears of COVID-19. Several events at [[McCormick Place]] have been canceled, and the [[Chicago Bulls]] and [[Chicago Blackhawks]] have suspended their seasons.<ref>[https://wgntv.com/news/coronavirus/chicago-businesses-hit-hard-by-covid-19-concerns/ Chicago businesses hit hard by COVID-19 concerns] WGN-TV, March 13, 2020</ref>\n\nBars and restaurants that sell liquor in [[Chicago]] were limited to 100 patrons on March 15.<ref>[https://wgntv.com/news/chicago-officials-announce-restrictions-for-bars-restaurants-that-sell-alcohol/ Chicago officials announce restrictions for bars, restaurants that sell alcohol] WGN-TV, March 15, 2020</ref> Governor JB Pritzker ordered all bars and restaurants in the state to close dining room service for two weeks beginning March 17. Deliveries, takeouts, and sidewalk service will still be permitted. The ruling came after Pritzker noticed that people were ignoring previous restrictions.<ref>[https://wgntv.com/news/coronavirus/all-bars-restaurants-to-be-closed-to-dine-in-customers-in-illinois-due-to-covid-19-concerns/ All bars, restaurants in Illinois to close their doors for 2 weeks due to COVID-19 concerns] Erik Runge, WGN-TV, March 15, 2020</ref>\n\n[[Oak Park, Illinois|Oak Park]] issued a shelter-in-place order effective March 20.<ref name=\"Wired Martineau\" />\n\n==Indiana==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Indiana}}\nOn March 6, Governor [[Eric Holcomb]] declared a public health emergency due to the first positive Indiana case.<ref>[https://www.wdrb.com/news/indiana-confirms-case-of-coronavirus-declares-public-health-emergency/article_92834a1e-5fbd-11ea-b311-b7179ddb59bd.html Indiana confirms case of coronavirus, declares public health emergency] [[WDRB]]</ref> Also on the 6th, [[Tippecanoe County]] declared a public health alert as testing for the virus started,<ref>[https://www.wthr.com/article/tippecanoe-county-health-department-tests-people-covid-19-virus-declares-public-health-alert Tippecanoe County Health Department tests people for COVID-19 virus, declares a public health alert] [[WTHR]]</ref> which was upgraded to a public health emergency on the 9th over a positive case.<ref>[https://www.wlfi.com/content/news/Tipp-Co-Health-Department-declaring-a-Public-Health-Emergency-568560941.html TIPP. CO. HEALTH DEPARTMENT DECLARED 'PUBLIC HEALTH EMERGENCY', ISSUES GUIDELINES] [[WLFI]]</ref>\n\nOn March 8, [[Eli Lilly and Company]] advised employees to work from home if at all possible, to help stop the spread of the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wishtv.com/news/local-news/lilly-employees-asked-to-work-from-home-if-possible-to-help-stop-spread-of-coronavirus/ |title=Lilly employees asked to work from home if possible to help stop spread of coronavirus |date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, Hickory Elementary School in [[Hendricks County]] closed for 2 weeks after a student tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wishtv.com/news/local-news/avon-elementary-student-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/ |title=Avon elementary student tests positive for coronavirus |date=March 8, 2020|access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Avon Community School Corporation later closed all [[Avon, Indiana|Avon]] schools until March 20 after a second student showed symptoms.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/2020/03/09/coronavirus-closes-avons-hickory-elementary/4998572002/ |title=Avon Schools close through March 20 after second student shows symptoms of the coronavirus |date=March 9, 2020|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[Indiana University]] announced classes at all campuses would be taught remotely for two weeks starting March 23, following spring break. In-person classes would potentially resume on April 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://president.iu.edu/speeches/statements/2020/03-10-coronavirus-letter |title=Urgent message from President Michael A. McRobbie: COVID-19 |date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Purdue University]] announces all classes to be held online starting March 23 and potentially through the end of the semester.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.purdue.edu/president/messages/campus-community/2020/2003-coronavirus-update-2.php |title=COVID-19 Update from President Daniels and Provost Akridge |date=March 10, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> On March 11, the [[University of Notre Dame]] announced classes would be taught online starting March 23 through at least April 13, and classes would be cancelled the week of April 15 to allow time to transition classes to an online format.<ref name=\"ND\">{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.nd.edu/news/father-jenkins-in-person-classes-suspended-moved-online/ |title=Father Jenkins: in-person classes suspended, moved online |date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> That same day, [[Ball State University]] announced that, starting March 15, classes would transition to online only until April 30.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bsu.edu/news/press-center/archives/2020/3/covid-19 |title=Statement about COVID-19 |website=bsu.edu}}</ref>\n\nHolcomb announced the closure of all bars and restaurants statewide to in-person service on March 16. Delivery, take-out, and drive-through service will still be available.<ref name=\"WDRB 3-16-2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wdrb.com/news/kentucky-and-indiana-bars-and-restaurants-to-close-dine-in/article_ef1eb27a-678a-11ea-8ad8-eb7927ad966a.html |title=Kentucky and Indiana bars and restaurants to close dine-in services |first=Marcus |last=Green |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=[[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville, KY]] |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> He imposed a stay-at-home order effective March 25 to April 7.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gov. Holcomb issues a 'stay at home' order|publisher=[[WTHR]]|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url=https://www.wthr.com/article/gov-holcomb-issues-stay-home-order}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Holcomb announced statewide [[stay-at-home order]] effective March 25.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indiana Gov. Eric Holcomb Issues 'Stay-at-Home' Order Amid Coronavirus Pandemic |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/coronavirus/indiana-gov-eric-holcomb-issues-stay-at-home-order-amid-coronavirus-pandemic/2242781/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=NBC Chicago |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On April 1, [[Marion County, Indiana|Marion County]] extended the stay-at-home order until May 1 within the county.<ref>{{cite news|title=Marion County to extend stay-at-home order through May 1, close golf courses beginning April 3|publisher=[[WXIN]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|url=https://fox59.com/news/coronavirus/marion-county-to-extend-stay-at-home-order-through-may-1-close-golf-courses-beginning-april-3/}}</ref>\n\n==Iowa==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iowa}}\n* March 9 \u2013 Proclamation of Disaster Emergency signed by Governor [[Kim Reynolds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weareiowa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/8-iowans-test-postivie-for-coronavirus-covid-19/524-982d69c7-c93d-4bac-b65c-96006fbc6ddb|title=32 test negative, 8 test postive for COVID-19|website=weareiowa.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*March 15 \u2013 Governor Reynolds recommends closing schools for four weeks. The state is developing legislation to provide child care during the emergency, including food for low-income students. The total number of confirmed coronavirus infections in the state increases to 22.<ref>[https://idph.iowa.gov/News/ArtMID/646/ArticleID/158307/Gov-Reynolds-recommends-Iowa-schools-close-for-four-weeks-will-hold-a-press-conference-tomorrow-31520 Gov. Reynolds recommends Iowa schools close for four weeks, will hold a press conference tomorrow (3/15/20)] Author: Polly Carver-Kimm, Iowa Department of Public Health, March 15, 2020</ref>\n*March 25 - Number of cases in Iowa reached 145, and one fatality reported in [[Dubuque County, Iowa|Dubuque County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcrg.com/content/news/21-additional-positive-COVID-19-cases-in-Iowa-569093311.html|title=21 additional positive COVID-19 cases in Iowa|last=Greene|first=Jay|website=www.kcrg.com|language=english|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*March 26 - Governor expands upon previous Covid-19 disaster proclamations to halt non-essential surgeries and dental procedures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/health/2020/03/26/iowa-governor-kim-reynolds-daily-covid-19-news-conference-coronavirus/2914636001/|title=Iowa orders additional retail closures, halts elective and nonessential surgeries and dental procedures|last=Richardson|first=Ian|website=Des Moines Register|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n*March 27 - Governor's office asserts:  \"[The] Proclamation suspends all nonessential or elective surgeries and procedures until April 16th, that includes surgical abortion procedures\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/health/2020/03/27/coronavirus-in-iowa-surgical-abortion-suspended-kim-reynolds-non-essential-surgery-proclamation/2930439001/|title=Governor's office says order suspending 'non-essential' surgery includes halting surgical abortions|last=Rodriguez|first=Barbara|website=Des Moines Register|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Kansas==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kansas#Government response}}\nOn March 12, Governor Laura Kelly has issued an emergency declaration for the State of Kansas.<ref>[https://governor.kansas.gov/governor-issues-emergency-declaration-for-covid-19/ Governor Issues Emergency Declaration for COVID-19] March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Johnson County has declared a state of emergency.<ref>[https://www.kwch.com/content/news/Welsey-Medical-Center-doctor-confirms-first-coronavirus-case-in-Wichita-568770071.html COVID-19 patient released from Wichita hospital] KWCH 12, March 14, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor [[Laura Kelly]] recommends closing schools for a week.<ref>[https://www.kwch.com/content/news/Kansas-Department-of-Education-recommends-closing-schools-to-develop-plan-for-COVID-19-568817091.html Gov. Kelly, Kansas Department of Education recommends schools close for one week] KWCH 12, March 15, 2020</ref> Several schools across the state (but none in Wichita) suspend classes for the rest of the month.<ref>[https://www.kwch.com/content/news/Geary-Co-Schools-close-additional-week-due-to-coronavirus-568779741.html School districts across Kansas suspend classes to combat coronavirus] KWCH 12, March 15, 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Kelly also announced a ban on gatherings of 50 or more people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leavenworthtimes.com/news/20200316/kelly-imposes-cdc-limit-of-50-people-at-gatherings-kansas-documents-11-cases |title=Kelly imposes CDC limit of 50 people at gatherings, Kansas documents 11 cases |last1=Carpenter |first1=Tim |website=The Leavenworth Times - Leavenworth, KS |language=en |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Johnson County, Kansas|Johnson]], [[Wyandotte County, Kansas|Wyandotte]], and [[Leavenworth County, Kansas|Leavenworth]] counties imposed stay-at-home orders on March 22.<ref name=\"KMBC Belton\" /> [[Douglas County, Kansas|Douglas County]] issued an order effective March 24 until April 23 at the earliest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Douglas County orders residents to 'stay at home' beginning Tuesday, in order similar to KC metro|work=[[Lawrence Journal-World]]|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www2.ljworld.com/news/general-news/2020/mar/22/douglas-county-issues-stay-at-home-order-similar-to-kc-metro/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, [[Miami County, Kansas|Miami County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 25 until April 23.\n\nOn March 24, [[Atchison County, Kansas|Atchison County]] issued a \"shelter-at-home order\" effective March 25 to April 25.<ref name=\"WDAF\">{{cite news|title=These counties in and around the KC metro have 'stay-at-home' orders|publisher=[[WDAF-TV]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://fox4kc.com/tracking-coronavirus/these-counties-in-and-around-the-kc-metro-have-stay-at-home-orders/}}</ref> [[Morris County, Kansas|Morris County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 25 until April 25.<ref>{{cite news|title=CORONAVIRUS: Morris County issues stay at home order effective Wednesday|first=Tagan|last=Trahoon|publisher=[[KVOE (AM)|KVOE]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.kvoe.com/news/item/47775-coronavirus-morris-county-issues-stay-at-home-order-effective-wednesday}}</ref> [[Sedgwick County, Kansas|Sedgwick County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 25. [[Doniphan County, Kansas|Doniphan]] and [[Shawnee County, Kansas|Shawnee]] counties issued stay-at-home orders effective March 26.<ref name=\"WIBW Shawnee\">{{cite news|title=Shawnee Co. issues safe-at-home order|publisher=[[WIBW-TV]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.wibw.com/content/news/Shawnee-Co-issues-stay-at-home-order-569071081.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, [[Lyon County, Kansas|Lyon County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 26 until April 25.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lyon Co. issues Stay at Home Order|publisher=[[WIBW-TV]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.wibw.com/content/news/Lyon-Co-issues-Stay-at-Home-Order-569092501.html}}</ref> [[Coffey County, Kansas|Coffey County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 26.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coffey Co. issues Stay at Home Order|publisher=[[WIBW-TV]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.wibw.com/content/news/Coffey-Co-issues-Stay-at-Home-Order-569093251.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, [[Sumner County, Kansas|Sumner County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 27 through April 25.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sumner County has first COVID-19 case, issues stay-at-home order|publisher=[[KSNW]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.ksn.com/news/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-in-kansas/sumner-county-issues-stay-at-home-order/}}</ref> [[Osage County, Kansas|Osage County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 28 until further notice.<ref>{{cite news|title=Osage County issues stay at home order over coronavirus|first=Mark|last=Feuerborn|publisher=[[KSNT]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.ksnt.com/health/coronavirus/osage-county-issues-stay-at-home-order-over-coronavirus/}}</ref> [[Jefferson County, Kansas|Jefferson County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective March 28 until April 14.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jefferson Co. issues Stay at Home Order|publisher=[[WIBW-TV]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.wibw.com/content/news/J