ocal/mayor-berke-to-announce-executive-order-thursday-that-suspends-dine-in-restaurant-service|title=Update: More local communities pass new COVID-19 restrictions|website=News Channel 9|language=en|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, the mayor of [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] issued an executive order closing bars, gyms, and commercial event venues and restricting restaurants to delivery and take-out service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wate.com/health/coronavirus/knoxville-mayor-kincannon-issues-executive-order-closing-bars-gyms-clubs-puts-limits-on-restaurants/|title=Knoxville Mayor Kincannon issues executive order closing bars, gyms, clubs; puts limits on restaurants|website=WATE|language=en|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Nashville's Metro Public Health Department issued a stay-at-home order effective for at least 14 days for Nashville and Davidson County.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cooper Issues Stay-at-Home Order |first=Kara |last=Hartnett |work=[[Nashville Scene]] |date=March 22, 2020 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |url=https://www.nashvillescene.com/news/pith-in-the-wind/article/21123674/cooper-issues-stayathome-order}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Safer At Home Order|work=Nashville COVID-19 Response|publisher=Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.asafenashville.org/safer-at-home-order/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Knoxville and [[Knox County, Tennessee|Knox County]] issued a stay-at-home order effective for at least 14 days beginning March 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wate.com/news/knox-county-closes-all-nonessential-businesses-with-safer-at-home-order/|title=Knox County closes all nonessential businesses with \u2018safer at home order\u2019|website=WATE|language=en|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] issued a \"safer-at-home order\" effective 