{"title_page": "Carole Cadwalladr", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Carole Cadwalladr\n| birth_name       = Carole Jane Cadwalladr\n| birth_date       = 1969 <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place      = [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]], England\n| occupation       = Journalist\n| education        = [[Radyr Comprehensive School]]\n|image  =Carole Cadwalladr 2019.jpg\n| alma_mater       = [[Hertford College, Oxford]]\n}}\n'''Carole Jane Cadwalladr''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u00e6|d|\u02c8|w|\u0252|l|\u0259|d|\u0259r}}; born 1969) is a British author, investigative journalist and features writer. She is a features writer for ''[[The Observer]]'' and formerly worked at ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/carolecadwalladr|title=Carole Cadwalladr|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 November 2017}}</ref> Cadwalladr rose to international prominence in 2018 when she exposed the [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica conspiracy theory]].\n\nCadwalladr was a finalist for the [[2019 Pulitzer Prize]] for National Reporting, alongside ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporters, for her coverage of the Cambridge Analytica scandal.\n\n==Early life==\nCadwalladr was born in [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]]<ref>https://www.findmypast.co.uk/search/results?datasetname=england+%26+wales+births+1837-2006&firstname=carole&lastname=cadwalladr</ref> educated at [[Radyr Comprehensive School]], [[Cardiff]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/24/our-political-elite-oxbridge-club|title=Whatever the party, our political elite is an Oxbridge club|first=Carole|last=Cadwalladr|work=The Guardian|date=24 August 2015|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> and [[Hertford College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hertford.ox.ac.uk/news/hertford-hugh-and-press-freedom|title=Hertford, Hugh, and Press Freedom|publisher=Hertford, College, Oxford University|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCadwalladr's [[debut novel|first novel]], ''The Family Tree'', was shortlisted for the 2006 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]], the [[Author's Club First Novel Award]], the [[Waverton Good Read Award]], and the [[Wales Book of the Year]]. It was also a ''[[Daily Mail]]'' Book Club pick and was dramatised as a five-part serial on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/1084/carole-cadwalladr|title=Carole Cadwalladr author biography|first=|last=BookBrowse|publisher=}}</ref> In the US, it was a ''[[New York Times Book Review]]'' Editor's Choice. ''The Family Tree'' was translated into several languages including Spanish, Italian, German, Czech, and Portuguese.\n\nAs a journalist, her work in the second decade of the twenty-first century has been about issues related to technology. She has for example, interviewed [[Jimmy Wales]], the founder of Wikipedia.<ref name=\"Walesint\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/07/jimmy-wales-wikipedia-interview |title=Wikipedia's Jimmy Wales: 'It's true, I'm not a billionaire. So?' \u2013 interview |last=Cadwalladr |first=Carole |date=7 October 2014 |work=The Guardian |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nStarting in late 2016 ''The Observer'' published an extensive series of articles by Cadwalladr about what she called the \"right-wing fake news ecosystem\".<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite news|last=Barnett|first=Anthony|url=http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2017/12/14/democracy-and-the-machinations-of-mind-control/|title=Democracy and the Machinations of Mind Control|work=New York Review of Books|date=14 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Anthony Barnett (writer)|Anthony Barnett]] wrote in the blog of ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' about Cadwalladr's articles in ''The Observer'', which have reported malpractice by campaigners for [[Brexit]], and the illicit funding of [[Vote Leave]], in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU membership referendum]]. She has also reported on alleged links between [[Nigel Farage]], the [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]] of [[Donald Trump]], and the Russian influence on the 2016 presidential election that has been investigated in the United States.<ref name=\"Barnett\"/> With regard to the Trump presidential campaign allegation, although the full report remains unpublished, the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]] reported that it had not found evidence that the Trump campaign had conspired with the Russian influence on the 2016 presidential election. Before [[Cambridge Analytica]] closed operations in 2018, the company took legal action against ''The Observer'' for the claims made in Cadwalladr's articles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/the-observer-fought-off-legal-threats-from-facebook-and-cambridge-analytica-before-publishing-data-harvesting-scoop/|title=The Observer fought off legal threats from Facebook and Cambridge Analytica|work=[[Press Gazette]]}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 Cadwalladr gave a fifteen-minute long [[TED (conference)|TED talk]] about the links between Facebook and Brexit, titled  ''\"Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy\"''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ted.com/talks/carole_cadwalladr_facebook_s_role_in_brexit_and_the_threat_to_democracy|title=Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy  {{!}} TED2019|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=2019-04-17|website=TED|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> According to Cadwalladr she delivered the talk directly to the people she described as \"'the Gods of Silicon Valley: [[Mark Zuckerberg]], [[Sheryl Sandberg]], [[Larry Page]], [[Sergey Brin]] and [[Jack Dorsey]]'. The founders of Facebook and Google \u2013 who were sponsoring the conference \u2013 and the co-founder of Twitter \u2013 who was speaking at it.\"<ref name=cconted>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/21/carole-cadwalladr-ted-tech-google-facebook-zuckerberg-silicon-valley |title=My TED talk: how I took on the tech titans in their lair |newspaper=The Observer |author=Carole Cadwalladr|date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> She summarised her speech in an article in ''The Observer'': \"as things stood, I didn\u2019t think it was possible to have free and fair elections ever again. That liberal democracy was broken. And they had broken it.\" The speech was applauded.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}} Some of the \"tech giants\" criticised complained about \"factual inaccuracies\", but when invited to specify them did not respond.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n[[Arron Banks]] has initiated libel action against her as of 12 July 2019 over her claims that he had a \"covert relationship\" with and had been offered money by the Russian Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://order-order.com/2019/07/12/banks-formally-files-libel-proceedings-cadwalladr/|title=Banks Formally Files Libel Proceedings Against Carole Cadwalladr -|date=12 July 2019|website=Guido Fawkes}}</ref>\n\n===Journalism awards===\n* British Journalism Awards\u2019 Technology Journalism Award in December 2017<ref>{{cite news|last=Slawson|first=Nicola|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/dec/12/guardian-observer-british-journalism-awards-press-gazette|title=Guardian and Observer scoop three prizes in British Journalism Awards\n|work=The Guardian|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mayhew|first=Freddy|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/british-journalism-awards-2017-nick-ferrari-is-journalist-of-the-year-full-list-of-winners/|title=British Journalism Awards 2017: Nick Ferrari is journalist of the year, Inside Housing named top news provider|work=Press Gazette|date=11 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> \n* Specialist journalist of the year 2017 at the national [[Society of Editors]] press awards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/mar/14/guardian-and-observer-journalists-win-nine-awards-at-press-awards|title=Guardian and Observer journalists win nine awards at Press Awards|first=Patrick|last=Greenfield|date=14 March 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* [[Orwell Prize]] for political journalism in June 2018 (for her work \"on the impact of [[big data]] on the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU Referendum]] and the 2016 US presidential election\").<ref>{{cite news|last=Orwell Foundation|url=https://www.orwellfoundation.com/the-orwell-foundation/news-events/news-events/news/winners-orwell-prize-2018/|title=Orwell Prize 2018: The Orwell Prize for Journalism|work=The Orwell Foundation|date=25 June 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Reporters Without Borders|Reporters without Borders]] \"L\u2019esprit de RSF\" award in November 2018 (for her work on subversion of democratic processes).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/observers-carole-cadwalladr-wins-reporters-without-borders-lesprit-de-rsf-award|title=The Observer\u2019s Carole Cadwalladr wins Reporters Without Borders\u2019 \u2018L\u2019esprit de RSF\u2019 award {{!}} Reporters without borders|website=RSF|language=fr-FR|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref>\n* The 2018 [[Polk Award]] for National Reporting with reporters from the New York Times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/19/us/politics/george-polk-awards.html|title=New York Times Wins Two George Polk Awards|first=Eileen|last=Sullivan|date=19 February 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* The 2018 [[Stieg Larsson Prize]], an annual award of 200,000 [[Swedish krona|krona]] for people working in [[Stieg Larrson]]'s spirit<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stieglarssonfoundation.se/the-annual-stieg-larsson-prize/|title=The annual Stieg Larsson prize|date=1 March 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Political Studies Association]] Journalist of the Year in November 2018 (joint award with [[Amelia Gentleman]]) for her persistence and resilience in pursuing \"investigative journalism on subjects such as personal data\".<ref name=\"PSA\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/nov/27/carole-cadwalladr-and-amelia-gentleman-win-joint-journalist-of-the-year-award |title=Amelia Gentleman and Carole Cadwalladr win joint journalist of the year award |last=Rawlinson |date=November 2018 |access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n* Two 2018 British Journalism Awards for Technology reporting and Investigation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/observers-carole-cadwalladr-award-wins-are-important-piece-of-armour-against-critics-who-attack-me-and-my-reporting/|title=Observer's Carole Cadwalladr: Award wins are 'important piece of armour' against critics who attack me and my reporting|first=Charlotte Tobitt|last=Twitter|date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n* Technology journalist of the year in the 2018 [[Society of Editors]] awards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/apr/03/national-press-awards-guardian-and-observer-win-for-windrush-and-cambridge-analytica|title=National Press Awards: Guardian and Observer win for Windrush and Cambridge Analytica|first=Guardian|last=staff|date=3 April 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* The 2019 [[Gerald Loeb Award]] for Investigative Reporting<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytco.com/press/times-wins-three-loeb-awards/|title=Times Wins Three Loeb Awards|date=1 July 2019|website=The New York Times Company}}</ref><ref name=LOEB-2019>{{Cite press release |title=UCLA Anderson School of Management Announces 2019 Gerald Loeb Award Winners |date=June 28, 2019 |publisher=UCLA Anderson School of Management |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ucla-anderson-school-of-management-announces-2019-gerald-loeb-award-winners-300877656.html |last1=Trounson |first1=Rebecca |access-date=October 2, 2019 |website=[[PR Newswire]]}}</ref>\n*The annual [[Hay Festival]]'s Medal for Journalism in May 2019, \"for the heroic and rigorous investigative journalism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hayfestival.com/medals|title=Medals \u2013 Hay Festival|website=www.hayfestival.com|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n*Finalist, [[2019 Pulitzer Prize]] for National Reporting, alongside ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporters, for her coverage of the Cambridge Analytica scandal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/staff-new-york-times-contributions-carole-cadwalladr-guardianthe-observer-london|title=The 2019 Pulitzer Prize Finalist in National Reporting|last=|first=|date=|website=The Pulitzer|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* {{Cite book|title=Lebanon (Travellers Survival Kit)|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=1996|publisher=Vacation Work|isbn=1854581473|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d_mW2yOhldgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Carole+Cadwalladr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF3Jj6j_rUAhXTCD4KHQiCDzEQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=Carole%20Cadwalladr&f=false|title=The Family Tree: A Novel|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=2005|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781440649516|language=en}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071022072745/http://www.metacritic.com/books/authors/cadwalladrcarole/familytree Collected reviews] of ''The Family Tree''\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/23/books/review/23OCONNER.html Review of ''The Family Tree''], by [[Patricia T. O'Conner]] in ''[[New York Times Review of Books]]'', 23 January 2005\n* [https://www.ted.com/speakers/carole_cadwalladr Carole Cadwalladr, Investigative journalist] ''TED'' April 2019\n* {{YouTube|id=OQSMr-3GGvQ|title=Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy}} published on 10 June 2019 with Cadwalladr\n* [https://www.npr.org/2018/07/19/630443485/reporter-shows-the-links-between-the-men-behind-brexit-and-the-trump-campaign \"The Links Between Russia, Trump And Brexit\"], an interview with Cadwalladr on [[NPR]]'s [[Fresh Air]]\n\n{{GeraldLoebAward Investigative}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cadwalladr, Carole}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:British women novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Radyr Comprehensive School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hertford College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Gerald Loeb Award winners for Investigative]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Carole Cadwalladr\n| birth_name       = Carole Jane Cadwalladr\n| birth_date       = 1969 <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place      = [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]], England\n| occupation       = Journalist\n| education        = [[Radyr Comprehensive School]]\n|image  =Carole Cadwalladr 2019.jpg\n| alma_mater       = [[Hertford College, Oxford]]\n}}\n'''Carole Jane Cadwalladr''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u00e6|d|\u02c8|w|\u0252|l|\u0259|d|\u0259r}}; born 1969) is a British author, investigative journalist and features writer. She is a features writer for ''[[The Observer]]'' and formerly worked at ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/carolecadwalladr|title=Carole Cadwalladr|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 November 2017}}</ref> Cadwalladr rose to international prominence in 2018 when she exposed the [[Facebook\u2013Cambridge Analytica data scandal]].\n\nCadwalladr was a finalist for the [[2019 Pulitzer Prize]] for National Reporting, alongside ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporters, for her coverage of the Cambridge Analytica scandal.\n\n==Early life==\nCadwalladr was born in [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]]<ref>https://www.findmypast.co.uk/search/results?datasetname=england+%26+wales+births+1837-2006&firstname=carole&lastname=cadwalladr</ref> educated at [[Radyr Comprehensive School]], [[Cardiff]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/24/our-political-elite-oxbridge-club|title=Whatever the party, our political elite is an Oxbridge club|first=Carole|last=Cadwalladr|work=The Guardian|date=24 August 2015|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> and [[Hertford College, Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hertford.ox.ac.uk/news/hertford-hugh-and-press-freedom|title=Hertford, Hugh, and Press Freedom|publisher=Hertford, College, Oxford University|date=28 November 2012|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCadwalladr's [[debut novel|first novel]], ''The Family Tree'', was shortlisted for the 2006 [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]], the [[Author's Club First Novel Award]], the [[Waverton Good Read Award]], and the [[Wales Book of the Year]]. It was also a ''[[Daily Mail]]'' Book Club pick and was dramatised as a five-part serial on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/1084/carole-cadwalladr|title=Carole Cadwalladr author biography|first=|last=BookBrowse|publisher=}}</ref> In the US, it was a ''[[New York Times Book Review]]'' Editor's Choice. ''The Family Tree'' was translated into several languages including Spanish, Italian, German, Czech, and Portuguese.\n\nAs a journalist, her work in the second decade of the twenty-first century has been about issues related to technology. She has for example, interviewed [[Jimmy Wales]], the founder of Wikipedia.<ref name=\"Walesint\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/feb/07/jimmy-wales-wikipedia-interview |title=Wikipedia's Jimmy Wales: 'It's true, I'm not a billionaire. So?' \u2013 interview |last=Cadwalladr |first=Carole |date=7 October 2014 |work=The Guardian |access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nStarting in late 2016 ''The Observer'' published an extensive series of articles by Cadwalladr about what she called the \"right-wing fake news ecosystem\".<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite news|last=Barnett|first=Anthony|url=http://www.nybooks.com/daily/2017/12/14/democracy-and-the-machinations-of-mind-control/|title=Democracy and the Machinations of Mind Control|work=New York Review of Books|date=14 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Anthony Barnett (writer)|Anthony Barnett]] wrote in the blog of ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' about Cadwalladr's articles in ''The Observer'', which have reported malpractice by campaigners for [[Brexit]], and the illicit funding of [[Vote Leave]], in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU membership referendum]]. She has also reported on alleged links between [[Nigel Farage]], the [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]] of [[Donald Trump]], and the Russian influence on the 2016 presidential election that has been investigated in the United States.<ref name=\"Barnett\"/> With regard to the Trump presidential campaign allegation, although the full report remains unpublished, the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Mueller investigation]] reported that it had not found evidence that the Trump campaign had conspired with the Russian influence on the 2016 presidential election. Before [[Cambridge Analytica]] closed operations in 2018, the company took legal action against ''The Observer'' for the claims made in Cadwalladr's articles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/the-observer-fought-off-legal-threats-from-facebook-and-cambridge-analytica-before-publishing-data-harvesting-scoop/|title=The Observer fought off legal threats from Facebook and Cambridge Analytica|work=[[Press Gazette]]}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 Cadwalladr gave a fifteen-minute long [[TED (conference)|TED talk]] about the links between Facebook and Brexit, titled  ''\"Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy\"''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ted.com/talks/carole_cadwalladr_facebook_s_role_in_brexit_and_the_threat_to_democracy|title=Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy  {{!}} TED2019|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=2019-04-17|website=TED|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> According to Cadwalladr she delivered the talk directly to the people she described as \"'the Gods of Silicon Valley: [[Mark Zuckerberg]], [[Sheryl Sandberg]], [[Larry Page]], [[Sergey Brin]] and [[Jack Dorsey]]'. The founders of Facebook and Google \u2013 who were sponsoring the conference \u2013 and the co-founder of Twitter \u2013 who was speaking at it.\"<ref name=cconted>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/apr/21/carole-cadwalladr-ted-tech-google-facebook-zuckerberg-silicon-valley |title=My TED talk: how I took on the tech titans in their lair |newspaper=The Observer |author=Carole Cadwalladr|date= 21 April 2019}}</ref> She summarised her speech in an article in ''The Observer'': \"as things stood, I didn\u2019t think it was possible to have free and fair elections ever again. That liberal democracy was broken. And they had broken it.\" The speech was applauded.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}} Some of the \"tech giants\" criticised complained about \"factual inaccuracies\", but when invited to specify them did not respond.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n[[Arron Banks]] has initiated libel action against her as of 12 July 2019 over her claims that he had a \"covert relationship\" with and had been offered money by the Russian Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://order-order.com/2019/07/12/banks-formally-files-libel-proceedings-cadwalladr/|title=Banks Formally Files Libel Proceedings Against Carole Cadwalladr -|date=12 July 2019|website=Guido Fawkes}}</ref>\n\n===Journalism awards===\n* British Journalism Awards\u2019 Technology Journalism Award in December 2017<ref>{{cite news|last=Slawson|first=Nicola|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/dec/12/guardian-observer-british-journalism-awards-press-gazette|title=Guardian and Observer scoop three prizes in British Journalism Awards\n|work=The Guardian|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mayhew|first=Freddy|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/british-journalism-awards-2017-nick-ferrari-is-journalist-of-the-year-full-list-of-winners/|title=British Journalism Awards 2017: Nick Ferrari is journalist of the year, Inside Housing named top news provider|work=Press Gazette|date=11 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> \n* Specialist journalist of the year 2017 at the national [[Society of Editors]] press awards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/mar/14/guardian-and-observer-journalists-win-nine-awards-at-press-awards|title=Guardian and Observer journalists win nine awards at Press Awards|first=Patrick|last=Greenfield|date=14 March 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* [[Orwell Prize]] for political journalism in June 2018 (for her work \"on the impact of [[big data]] on the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|EU Referendum]] and the 2016 US presidential election\").<ref>{{cite news|last=Orwell Foundation|url=https://www.orwellfoundation.com/the-orwell-foundation/news-events/news-events/news/winners-orwell-prize-2018/|title=Orwell Prize 2018: The Orwell Prize for Journalism|work=The Orwell Foundation|date=25 June 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Reporters Without Borders|Reporters without Borders]] \"L\u2019esprit de RSF\" award in November 2018 (for her work on subversion of democratic processes).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/news/observers-carole-cadwalladr-wins-reporters-without-borders-lesprit-de-rsf-award|title=The Observer\u2019s Carole Cadwalladr wins Reporters Without Borders\u2019 \u2018L\u2019esprit de RSF\u2019 award {{!}} Reporters without borders|website=RSF|language=fr-FR|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref>\n* The 2018 [[Polk Award]] for National Reporting with reporters from the New York Times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/19/us/politics/george-polk-awards.html|title=New York Times Wins Two George Polk Awards|first=Eileen|last=Sullivan|date=19 February 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n* The 2018 [[Stieg Larsson Prize]], an annual award of 200,000 [[Swedish krona|krona]] for people working in [[Stieg Larrson]]'s spirit<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stieglarssonfoundation.se/the-annual-stieg-larsson-prize/|title=The annual Stieg Larsson prize|date=1 March 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Political Studies Association]] Journalist of the Year in November 2018 (joint award with [[Amelia Gentleman]]) for her persistence and resilience in pursuing \"investigative journalism on subjects such as personal data\".<ref name=\"PSA\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/nov/27/carole-cadwalladr-and-amelia-gentleman-win-joint-journalist-of-the-year-award |title=Amelia Gentleman and Carole Cadwalladr win joint journalist of the year award |last=Rawlinson |date=November 2018 |access-date=7 December 2018}}</ref>\n* Two 2018 British Journalism Awards for Technology reporting and Investigation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/observers-carole-cadwalladr-award-wins-are-important-piece-of-armour-against-critics-who-attack-me-and-my-reporting/|title=Observer's Carole Cadwalladr: Award wins are 'important piece of armour' against critics who attack me and my reporting|first=Charlotte Tobitt|last=Twitter|date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n* Technology journalist of the year in the 2018 [[Society of Editors]] awards<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/apr/03/national-press-awards-guardian-and-observer-win-for-windrush-and-cambridge-analytica|title=National Press Awards: Guardian and Observer win for Windrush and Cambridge Analytica|first=Guardian|last=staff|date=3 April 2019|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n* The 2019 [[Gerald Loeb Award]] for Investigative Reporting<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytco.com/press/times-wins-three-loeb-awards/|title=Times Wins Three Loeb Awards|date=1 July 2019|website=The New York Times Company}}</ref><ref name=LOEB-2019>{{Cite press release |title=UCLA Anderson School of Management Announces 2019 Gerald Loeb Award Winners |date=June 28, 2019 |publisher=UCLA Anderson School of Management |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ucla-anderson-school-of-management-announces-2019-gerald-loeb-award-winners-300877656.html |last1=Trounson |first1=Rebecca |access-date=October 2, 2019 |website=[[PR Newswire]]}}</ref>\n*The annual [[Hay Festival]]'s Medal for Journalism in May 2019, \"for the heroic and rigorous investigative journalism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hayfestival.com/medals|title=Medals \u2013 Hay Festival|website=www.hayfestival.com|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n*Finalist, [[2019 Pulitzer Prize]] for National Reporting, alongside ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporters, for her coverage of the Cambridge Analytica scandal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/finalists/staff-new-york-times-contributions-carole-cadwalladr-guardianthe-observer-london|title=The 2019 Pulitzer Prize Finalist in National Reporting|last=|first=|date=|website=The Pulitzer|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* {{Cite book|title=Lebanon (Travellers Survival Kit)|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=1996|publisher=Vacation Work|isbn=1854581473|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d_mW2yOhldgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Carole+Cadwalladr&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF3Jj6j_rUAhXTCD4KHQiCDzEQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=Carole%20Cadwalladr&f=false|title=The Family Tree: A Novel|last=Cadwalladr|first=Carole|date=2005|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9781440649516|language=en}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071022072745/http://www.metacritic.com/books/authors/cadwalladrcarole/familytree Collected reviews] of ''The Family Tree''\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/23/books/review/23OCONNER.html Review of ''The Family Tree''], by [[Patricia T. O'Conner]] in ''[[New York Times Review of Books]]'', 23 January 2005\n* [https://www.ted.com/speakers/carole_cadwalladr Carole Cadwalladr, Investigative journalist] ''TED'' April 2019\n* {{YouTube|id=OQSMr-3GGvQ|title=Facebook's role in Brexit \u2014 and the threat to democracy}} published on 10 June 2019 with Cadwalladr\n* [https://www.npr.org/2018/07/19/630443485/reporter-shows-the-links-between-the-men-behind-brexit-and-the-trump-campaign \"The Links Between Russia, Trump And Brexit\"], an interview with Cadwalladr on [[NPR]]'s [[Fresh Air]]\n\n{{GeraldLoebAward Investigative}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cadwalladr, Carole}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:British women novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Radyr Comprehensive School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hertford College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Gerald Loeb Award winners for Investigative]]\n", "name_user": "79.79.156.81", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carole_Cadwalladr"}
{"title_page": "Nosedive (Black Mirror)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = Nosedive\n| series = [[Black Mirror]]\n| image = [[File:Black Mirror - Nosedive.jpg|280px]]\n| caption = Lacie ([[Bryce Dallas Howard]]) gives a rating using her phone. The episode's pastel colours distinguish it from most ''Black Mirror'' episodes.\n| series_no = 3\n| episode = 1\n| story = [[Charlie Brooker]]\n| teleplay = [[Michael Schur]]<br> [[Rashida Jones]]\n| director = [[Joe Wright]]\n| photographer = [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| length = 63 minutes\n| release_date = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|10|21}}\n| guests =\n* [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] as Lacie Pound\n* [[Alice Eve]] as Naomi Blestow\n* [[Cherry Jones]] as Susan\n* [[James Norton (actor)|James Norton]] as Ryan Pound\n* [[Alan Ritchson]] as Paul\n* [[Daisy Haggard]] as Bets\n* [[Susannah Fielding]] as Carol\n* [[Michaela Coel]] as Airline Stewardess\n* [[Kadiff Kirwan]] as Chester\n* [[Sope Dirisu|\u1e62\u1ecdp\u1eb9\u0301 D\u00ecr\u00eds\u00f9]] as Man in Jail\n* Andrew Roux as Electro Station Attendant\n| prev = [[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\n| next = [[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\n| episode_list = List of Black Mirror episodes\n}}\n\n\"'''Nosedive'''\" is the first episode in the third series of the British science fiction [[anthology series]] ''[[Black Mirror]]''. [[Michael Schur]] and [[Rashida Jones]] wrote the teleplay for the episode, based on a story by series creator and co-showrunner [[Charlie Brooker]], while [[Joe Wright]] acted as director. It premiered on [[Netflix]] on 21 October 2016, alongside the rest of the third series.\n\nThe episode is set in a world where people can rate each other from one to five stars for every interaction they have, which can impact their [[socioeconomic status]]. Lacie ([[Bryce Dallas Howard]]) is a young woman overly obsessed with her ratings; she finds an opportunity to elevate her ratings greatly and move into a more luxurious residence after being chosen by her popular childhood friend ([[Alice Eve]]) as the maid of honour for her wedding. Her obsession leads to several mishaps on her journey to the wedding that culminate in a rapid reduction in her ratings.\n\nUnder Netflix, the episode was given a much larger budget than the previous episodes of the programme, when it had been under [[Channel 4]]. Brooker wrote an outline for the episode, then Schur wrote the former half of the episode and Jones wrote the latter. Production was undertaken in a manner similar to a short film; \"Nosedive\" was filmed in [[South Africa]], with [[Seamus McGarvey]] as [[director of photography]] and Joel Collins and James Foster as the [[production designers]]. The tone of the episode is less bleak and more comedic than other ''Black Mirror'' episodes, with the ending significantly more positive than in episodes of the programme's prior two series.\n\nThe episode received mainly positive reviews and is middling in critics' lists of ''Black Mirror'' episodes, qualitatively. The pastel visual aesthetics were widely praised, along with [[Max Richter]]'s soundtrack and Howard's performance. A criticism from several reviewers was the episode's predictability and ending, though the script and comedic undertones were praised by some. Many critics noted the similarity of the episode to real world app [[Peeple (mobile application)|Peeple]] and China's upcoming [[Social Credit System]], along with fictional works about social media with themes of gender and obsession with image. The episode was nominated for several awards, including a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] nomination for Howard and a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for McGarvey. A board game ''Nosedive'', based on the episode, was released in 2018.\n\n==Plot==\nSociety has embraced a technology wherein everyone shares their daily activities through eye implants and mobile devices and rates their interactions with others on a scale of one to five stars, cumulatively affecting everyone's [[socioeconomic status]].\n\nLacie Pound ([[Bryce Dallas Howard]]) seeks to raise her 4.2 rating to 4.5 for a discount on a luxury apartment; however, despite her attempts to be an outgoing and pleasant socialite, her rating has plateaued. Lacie talks to a consultant who suggests gaining favour from very highly-rated people. Lacie uploads a photograph of Mr. Rags, a ragdoll that she and her childhood friend Naomi ([[Alice Eve]]) made together. Naomi, who is currently rated 4.8, rates the photo five stars and calls Lacie, saying that she is engaged and inviting Lacie to deliver a speech as the maid of honour. Lacie agrees and commits on the apartment, anticipating many high ratings from the guests.\n\nOn the day of her flight, several mishaps cause people to rate Lacie negatively, dropping her rating below 4.2. At the airport, her flight is cancelled and she cannot buy a seat with her current rating. When Lacie causes a scene, security penalizes her by subtracting a full point for 24 hours. Because of her low rating, Lacie can only rent an older car to drive to the wedding, which she cannot recharge when it runs out of power. She is forced to hitchhike with Susan ([[Cherry Jones]]), a truck driver rated below 2.0. Susan tells Lacie that she used to care about her rating until her late husband was passed over for vital cancer treatment because their scores were deemed not high enough; she says she feels much freer without obsessing over ratings.\n\nThe next day, while Lacie is en route to the wedding, Naomi tells her to not come, as her severely reduced rating will negatively impact Naomi's own ratings. Enraged, Lacie reaches the wedding and sneaks in during the reception. She grabs the microphone and starts giving the speech she had written but becomes more and more upset, finally grabbing a knife and threatening to behead Mr. Rags. The guests rate Lacie negatively, causing her rating to fall below one star. Security arrives and arrests Lacie. She is taken to prison, and the technology supporting the rating system is removed from her eyes. She and the man in the cell opposite hers ([[Sope Dirisu]]) realise they can now speak without worrying about being rated, and gleefully hurl insults at each other.\n\n==Production==\n{{external media\n|video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jDiYGjp5iFg Black Mirror \u2013 Season 3]<br>The trailer for series three of ''Black Mirror''.\n|video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R32qWdOWrTo Black Mirror \u2013 Nosedive Featurette]<br>Brief commentary by Charlie Brooker and Bryce Dallas Howard.\n}}\n\"Nosedive\" is the first episode of the third series of ''Black Mirror''; all six episodes in this series were released on Netflix simultaneously on 21 October 2016. Brooker says it was selected to be the season premiere \"partly to slightly ease people in\",<ref name=\"worst year ever\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview-release-date-joe-wright-nosedive-shut-up-and-dance-a7372841.html|title=Black Mirror co-creator Charlie Brooker: 'I'm loath to say this is the worst year ever because the next is coming'|date=21 October 2016|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> at Netflix's recommendation.<ref name=\"ibm\"/> Alongside \"[[San Junipero]]\", \"Nosedive\" was first shown in 2016 ahead of its Netflix release at the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"collider\"/> Two days prior to the series' release on Netflix, Brooker hinted that \"Nosedive\" is \"a pastel, playful satire about modern insecurity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/black-mirror/44587/black-mirror-series-3-interview-charlie-brooker-and-annabel-jones|title=Black Mirror series 3 interview: Charlie Brooker and Annabel Jones|work=Den of Geek!|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|last=Mellor|first=Louisa|date=19 October 2016|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhilst series one and two of ''Black Mirror'' were shown on [[Channel 4]] in the UK, in September 2015 Netflix commissioned the series for 12 episodes (split into two series of six episodes),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-black-mirror-new-episodes-1201602037/|title=Netflix Picks Up 'Black Mirror' for 12 New Episodes|first=Debra |last=Birnbaum|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=25 September 2016|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> and in March 2016 it outbid Channel 4 for the rights to distributing the third series, with a bid of $40 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/mar/29/netflix-channel-4-charlie-brooker-black-mirror |title=Netflix deals Channel 4 knockout blow over Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror |first=John |last=Plunkett |date=29 March 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Due to its move to Netflix, the show had a larger budget than in previous series,<ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/> which one critic suggests is responsible for the \"impressive line-up\" that was noted by many reviewers.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Another critic called this episode the show's \"most ambitious yet\";<ref name=\"Independent Community\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-3-episode-nosedive-community-meow-meow-beanz-a7376651.html|title=Black Mirror season 3 episode 'Nosedive' is very similar to Community episode 'App Development and Condiments'|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> due to its larger episode order, series 3 was also able to vary its genre and tone more than previous series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/21/arts/television/review-black-mirror-finds-terror-and-soul-in-the-machine.html|title=Review: 'Black Mirror' Finds Terror, and Soul, in the Machine|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> One reviewer also noted that \"Nosedive\" contained \"only American characters\".<ref name=\"collider\"/>\n\nIn November 2016, to tie in with the episode, Netflix released a tongue-in-cheek app called Rate Me. The app allows users to rate people, by their [[Twitter]] handle, and view their own rating and the ratings of others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/rate-me-nosedive-black-mirror-netflix|title=Black Mirror's horrific people-rating app is now a reality. Sort of|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|last=Temperton|first=James|date=10 November 2016|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conception and writing===\n{{multiple image|align=left|total_width=250|image1=Rashida Jones at 2017 MIFF.jpg|height1=3000|width1=2151|image2=Michael Schur 2012 (cropped).jpg|height2=621|width2=497|footer=[[Rashida Jones]] and [[Michael Schur]], who co-wrote the script for \"Nosedive\".}}\nThe episode is based on an idea by series creator [[Charlie Brooker]] for a movie; he and executive producer [[Annabel Jones]] pitched the idea to several movie companies in the United States after the first series of ''Black Mirror'', but it was not commissioned.<ref name=\"ibm\">{{cite book | title = Inside Black Mirror | date = November 2018 | first1 = Charlie | last1 = Brooker | first2 = Annabel | last2 = Jones | first3 = Jason | last3 = Arnopp | chapter = Nosedive | isbn = 9781984823489 | publisher = [[Crown Publishing Group]] | place = New York City }}</ref> The original idea was of a comedy similar to ''[[Brewster's Millions]]'', focused on a high status person trying to reduce their ranking in 24 hours.<ref name=\"ibm\"/><ref name=\"Decider\"/> Later, Brooker wrote either a three<ref name=\"ew interview\"/> or four<ref name=\"avclub interview\"/> page outline for the episode, wanting it to be \"comedic, darkly\".<ref name=\"ew interview\"/> This version took inspiration from 1987 film ''[[Planes, Trains and Automobiles]]'', in which the character is on a journey\u2014for \"Nosedive\", this was initially a character travelling to an important work presentation.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>\n\n[[Rashida Jones]] and [[Michael Schur]] wrote the episode. Known for comedy and sitcoms, the pair had previously worked together on many shows, including ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'', but had never written anything together before \"Nosedive\".<ref name=\"avclub interview\"/> A fan of Brooker's works, Rashida Jones had been in contact with him for a few years beforehand and after the programme's move to Netflix, he suggested that she could write an episode. Schur was also a fan of ''Black Mirror'' and Rashida Jones suggested that they could co-write the episode. With Jones and Schur on board, the main character changed from someone focused on playing the ratings system to a people-pleaser, the work presentation was changed to a wedding and the idea of Lacie having a childhood talisman was introduced. Lacie's brother was originally an ex-boyfriend.<ref name=\"ibm\"/> Schur wrote the first half of the episode (up to Lacie beginning her travel in a rented car), while Rashida Jones wrote the second half, and the two then combined their scripts.<ref name=\"avclub interview\"/> In the initial draft, the episode ended with Lacie's work presentation going viral and her achieving fame. The final version of the ending showed Lacie in a jail cell, the rating device removed from her, allowing her to find freedom. An unused idea was that of rage rooms, where characters would go to destroy things to let out their anger.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Schur had an account on [[Twitter]] but not [[Facebook]] or [[Instagram]], as \"there's a bunch of strangers talking shit about you in there\", and Jones expressed a similarly negative attitude, stating \"I do have very strong, very conflicted feelings about rating systems and social media.\"<ref name=\"avclub interview\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.avclub.com/rashida-jones-and-michael-schur-talk-about-bringing-fun-1798254169|title=Rashida Jones and Michael Schur talk about bringing funny to ''Black Mirror''|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Zuckerman|first=Esther|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> Brooker notes that \"you are rewarded for having a more extreme opinion\" on social media; in the episode, as on the internet, almost all ratings given are either one or five stars.<ref name=\"slate interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2016/10/21/the_stars_and_writers_of_black_mirror_on_the_disturbing_new_season.html|title=''Black Mirror''{{'}}s Stars and Writers on How They Made the Most Disturbing Season Yet|last=Adams|first=Sam|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> Similarly, Schur opines that social media causes people to exaggerate their behaviour, particularly their rudeness.<ref name=\"time\"/> Jones believes that the episode, as with all ''Black Mirror'' episodes, \"pushes you into the near future\", while Schur considers it to be more of a \"parallel reality\". Brooker has described the episode as \"like a cross between ''[[Pleasantville (film)|Pleasantville]]'' and ''[[The Truman Show]]''\".<ref name=\"ew interview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/23/black-mirror-postmortem-interview-season-3|title=Black Mirror postmortem: Showrunner talks season 3 twists|date=21 October 2016|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref> Jones says the idea that \"women are taught to be liked, and men are taught to be powerful\", credited to [[Sheryl Sandberg]], is relevant to the episode, with Schur agreeing that Lacie's gender is important to the story,<ref name=\"slate interview\"/> though Schur notes that edited images on social media are causing negative [[body image]] issues for men as well.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4538883/black-mirror-netflix-rashida-jones-mike-schur/|title=Rashida Jones and Mike Schur's ''Black Mirror'' Episode Will Make You Rethink How You Use Social Media|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|last=Dockterman|first=Eliana|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Joe Wright by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Joe Wright]], the episode's director]]\nThe episode was the third in series three to be filmed.<ref name=\"ibm\"/> [[Joe Wright]] directed the episode, [[Seamus McGarvey]] was [[director of photography]] and the production designers, working for [[VFX]] company Painting Practice, were Joel Collins<ref name=\"creative review\"/> and James Foster.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/awards/joe-wright-relished-polyester-fabric-black-mirror-after-period-films-1202460842/|title=Joe Wright Relished the Chance to Go Polyester in 'Black Mirror'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Tobias|first=Scott|date=12 June 2017|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref> The episode was shot in four weeks<ref name=\"variety\"/> in [[Knysna]], [[South Africa]],<ref name=\"ibm\"/> a coastal town five hours (by car) from [[Cape Town]] chosen as it felt like an American coastal town.<ref name=\"creative review\"/><ref name=\"ibm\"/> Series three episode \"[[San Junipero]]\" was also filmed in South Africa.<ref name=\"creative review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.creativereview.co.uk/designing-black-mirror-interview-production-designer-joel-collins/|title=Black Mirror production designer Joel Collins on bringing Charlie Brooker's dystopian visions to life|work=[[Creative Review]]|last=Steven|first=Rachael|url-access=registration|date=16 November 2016|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', McGarvey noted that the episode was shot in [[4K resolution]] at the request of Netflix; he said the [[colour scheme]] was a mixture of [[wikt:duck-egg blue|duck-egg blue]], \"peppermint green\" and \"strange [[peach (color)|peach colors]]\", and that props and \"even the drinks people are drinking\" were chosen with care to create a \"sickly pastel feel\".<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/awards/emmys-black-mirror-seamus-mcgarvey-interview-1202520496/|title='Black Mirror' DP Seamus McGarvey Talks About Finding the 'Photographic Heart' of 'Nosedive'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|date=16 August 2017|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> Wright said that he made almost no changes to the script's dialogue.<ref name=\"nofilmschool\">{{cite podcast|url=https://nofilmschool.com/2017/07/black-mirror-joe-wright-and-owen-harris|title='Black Mirror': How Directors Joe Wright and Owen Harris Built Dystopian Worlds That Look Like Our Own [PODCAST]|website=No Film School|last=Fusco|first=Jon|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> Brooker has said that Wright's pastel treatment was a \"very strong visual idea that we had not foreseen\".<ref name=\"independent podcast\">{{cite podcast|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/charlie-brooker-interview-black-mirror-season-4-twitter-episode-writer-westworld-screenwriting-a8090086.html|title=Charlie Brooker interview: Black Mirror creator on season 4, plot option paralysis and being on Twitter less|website=[[The Independent]]|last=Hooton|first=Christopher|date=4 December 2017|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrooker pointed out that directors of ''Black Mirror'' episodes (in this case, Wright) have more \"power\" than in serialised television shows, as \"it is like making a short film\", and he said that Wright had \"been feeling quite bruised after doing ''[[Pan (2015 film)|Pan]]'', and [''Black Mirror''] was a good thing for him to get his teeth into which wasn't the full five-year commitment of a movie\".<ref name=\"worst year ever\"/> McGarvey had previously worked with Wright.<ref name=\"variety\"/> Watching [[dailies|rushes]] from the filming, Brooker was initially sceptical about Wright's saccharine style, but began to understand it as the filming progressed and the music was added.<ref name=\"independent podcast\"/> The scenes in which Lacie is driving utilise a [[computer-generated imagery|computer-generated]] landscape designed by Dan May, the episode's art director.<ref name=\"creative review\"/> She was initially planned to drive through multiple landscapes such as a desert, but this was changed for budget reasons.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>\n\nBryce Dallas Howard plays Lacie, the episode's main character. She was suggested by Wright, who auditioned her a decade previously for ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]''.<ref name=\"nofilmschool\"/> Howard gained {{convert|30|lb|kg}} for the role, saying in an interview with ''[[Marie Claire]]'' that body shaming is a \"huge part of the subtext of the story\".<ref name=\"marie claire\"/> She chose a laugh for Lacie which mixed \"fear\", \"disingenuousness\" and \"depression\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/> Howard first joined social media during Thanksgiving 2015 and was approached with the [[film treatment|treatment]] of the episode a fortnight later, in December 2015.<ref name=\"marie claire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/news/a23270/bryce-dallas-howard-black-mirror-interview/|title=Bryce Dallas Howard on Body Image, Social Media, and Gaining 30 Pounds for 'Black Mirror'|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|work=[[Marie Claire]]|date=26 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cosmopolitan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a7666694/black-mirror-bryce-dallas-howard-alice-eve-nosedive-interview/|title=Black Mirror Stars on the Terrifying Episode That May Make You Delete Your Instagram|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|last=Dibdin|first=Emma|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nChosen by Wright to compose the episode's soundtrack,<ref name=\"independent podcast\"/> [[Max Richter]] is a self-described \"conservatoire, university-trained classical composer\".<ref name=\"Richter Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/11/max-richter-interview-black-mirror-the-leftovers-miss-sloane/506033/|title=Max Richter's Soundtrack to Dystopia|work=[[The Atlantic]]|last=Gilbert|first=Sophie|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> Richter first met the director, Joe Wright, in London before the shooting of the episode had been completed and began coming up with ideas for the score. Richter aimed to \"support\" the episode's display of \"incredible anxiety hovering beneath this smiley surface ... while at the same time not flattening out the emotionality of it\", commenting in an interview that Wright's camerawork had a \"dream-like quality\" and that Brooker's \"story was fantastic\".<ref name=\"Richter Fact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/10/27/max-richter-soundtrack-black-mirror-nosedive/|title=Black Mirror composer Max Richter on soundtracking society's social media meltdown|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|last=Warwick|first=Oli|date=27 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> In another interview, Richter said he was aiming for the episode to have \"warmth and a fairytale quality throughout\" with \"darkness underneath it\", and notes that his composition was based on \"the sentiment and the emotional trajectory of the characters\". Richter also composed the sound effects which play when one character rates another, and incorporated these sounds into the score itself.<ref name=\"Richter Atlantic\"/>\n\n==Analysis==\nSeveral critics compared the episode to a 2014 episode of ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'', \"[[App Development and Condiments]]\", which features an app where users assign each other \"Meow Meow Beenz\" ratings on a scale from one to five; Jack Shepherd of ''[[The Independent]]'' notes that both episodes \"critically [analyse] people's obsession with stature on social media platforms with rating systems\".<ref name=\"Independent Community\"/> Other reviewers compared \"Nosedive\" to the [[mobile application]] [[Peeple (mobile application)|Peeple]],<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Sophie|title='Black Mirror' Is Back: 'Nosedive' Is a Sharp Satire About Social Media|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/10/black-mirror-nosedive-review-season-three-netflix/504668/|accessdate=22 October 2016|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=21 October 2016}}</ref> in which users could rate one another, that garnered immediate backlash upon its release.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/><ref name=\"Decider\"/> Brooker said in an interview that he was not aware of the ''Community'' episode when he came up with the idea for \"Nosedive\", but that he did see advertising for Peeple during pre-production, initially thinking it would turn out to be marketing for a comedy show, and he considered whether or not they should still produce the episode.<ref name=\"Decider\">{{cite web|url=http://decider.com/2016/10/27/black-mirror-nosedive-did-not-steal-from-community-interview/|title=Did 'Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker Know About That 'Community' Episode When He Made \"Nosedive\"?|last=Cobb|first=Kayla|work=Decider|publisher=[[New York Post]]|date=27 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> The episode has also been compared to the 2003 novel ''[[Down and Out in the Magic Kingdom]]'', as each work explores a link between social approval and power.<ref name=\"verge\"/>\n\nManuel Betancourt of ''[[Pacific Standard]]'' explains how \"Nosedive\" fits with other portrayals of social media in television and film, comparing it to 2017 films ''[[The Circle (2017 film)|The Circle]]'' and ''[[Ingrid Goes West]]'', which both explore negative aspects of social media. Betancourt says that historically, women have been portrayed as victims of technology, a pattern which these works fit. For instance, Ingrid and Lacie are both obsessed with coming across as perfect online. In contrast, male characters are traditionally the voice of reason: in these works, Lacie's brother Ryan, Mercer (''The Circle'') and Taylor's husband (''Ingrid Goes West'') serve this purpose.<ref name=\"pacific\"/> Furthermore, the androgyny of \"Nosedive\" character Susan is linked to her disdain for social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailytitan.com/2017/04/female-gaze-black-mirror-explores-gendered-expectations-social-media/|title=The Female Gaze: 'Black Mirror' explores the gendered expectations of social media|work=[[The Daily Titan]]|last=Casas|first=Darlene|date=11 April 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Betancourt writes that these characterisations do not accord with research on how men and women use technology, where some studies report that men have more emotional investment in positive feedback on social media. However, \"Nosedive\" shows people of all genders placing importance in social media, leading Betancourt to call it \"perhaps the most keen-eyed critique [...] of recent titles\".<ref name=\"pacific\">{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/social-justice/why-are-so-many-ladies-insta-fiends-in-movies|title=Why Does Hollywood Tell So Many Stories About Women Obsessed With Social Media?|work=[[Pacific Magazine]]|last=Betancourt|first=Manuel|date=11 August 2017|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nA ''[[Business Insider]]'' article by Erin Brodwin notes that the episode shows Lacie fall victim to the [[hedonic treadmill]]. Despite momentary happiness when receiving a high rating, Lacie is \"lonely and unsatisfied\". Brodwin points out that scientific studies concur with Lacie's experience, because there is no correlation between using social media and being happy in the long-term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/psychology-black-mirror-nosedive-social-media-2016-10|title=What psychology actually says about the tragically social-media obsessed society in 'Black Mirror'|work=[[Business Insider]]|last=Brodwin|first=Erin|date=27 October 2016|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nCritics have also noted the inclusion of [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]] within ''Black Mirror''&nbsp;\u2013 small details referring to other episodes. In \"Nosedive\", there is a frame where a social media post from Michael Callow reads, \"Just got thrown out of the zoo again :(\", a joke based on Callow having intercourse with a pig in \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/22898-black-mirror-season-3-easter-eggs|title=Every Single 'Black Mirror' Season 3 Easter Egg|work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]]|last=Hutchinson|first=Sean|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> Brooker has described this Easter egg as his favourite in series three.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://decider.com/2016/11/03/netflix-black-mirror-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview/|title='Black Mirror' Creators Talk About Season Three's Easter Eggs And What Your Favorite Episode Says About You|last=Cobb|first=Kayla|work=Decider|publisher=[[New York Post]]|date=3 November 2016|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> Another reference to that episode is the fictional show ''Sea of Tranquility''; in \"The National Anthem\", a special effects expert mentions having worked on the show, while in \"Nosedive\", Lacie hitchhikes with fans of the show. Additionally, in \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\", a news ticker contains the term \"Reputelligent\", which is the name of the company that Lacie consults for advice about her rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/black-mirror-easter-eggs-theory/|title=24 Easter Eggs From All Three Seasons of 'Black Mirror', Plus a Timeline Connecting Every Episode|work=ScreenCrush|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|last=Whitney|first=Erin Oliver|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Comparisons to Social Credit System===\n\"Nosedive\" has been widely compared to China's [[Social Credit System]], a governmental initiative planned for testing in 2020,<ref name=\"nme SCS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/tv/black-mirrors-nosedive-episode-become-reality-china-2263309|title=Black Mirror's 'Nosedive' episode is about to become reality in China|last=Connick|first=Tom|work=[[NME]]|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> and existing Chinese reputation systems such as [[Sesame Credit]].<ref name=\"dog SCS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/black-mirror/45041/how-black-mirror-series-3-is-eerily-coming-true|title=How Black Mirror series 3 is eerily coming true|work=[[Den of Geek!]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|last=Leane|first=Rob|date=3 November 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BM&Philosophy\">{{Citation|last=Urue\u00f1a|first=Sergio|title=Nosedive and the Anxieties of Social Media|date=2019|work=Black Mirror and Philosophy|pages=81\u201391|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd|language=en|doi=10.1002/9781119578291.ch8|isbn=978-1-119-57829-1|last2=Melikyan|first2=Nonna}}</ref> In November 2016, the Facebook page for ''Black Mirror'' shared an article in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' about the Social Credit System.{{efn|group=note|The article shared was the following: {{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20/1cd0dd9c-9516-11e6-ae9d-0030ac1899cd_story.html|title=China's plan to organize its society relies on 'big data' to rate everyone|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=22 October 2016}}}} The system would assign each citizen a score determining decisions such as \"whether you can borrow money\" or \"get your children into the best schools\", and that actions such as \"defaulting on a loan\" or \"criticizing the ruling party\" would lead to a lower score. The existing Sesame Credit system, which assigns users scores between 350 and 950,<ref name=\"tele SCS\"/> already allowed some people with high scores to rent vehicles without a deposit, or pay to skip hospital queues.<ref name=\"dog SCS\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20|title=China's plan to organize its society relies on 'big data' to rate everyone|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, a person's score in Sesame Credit is dependent on the scores of the people in their social circle.<ref name=\"tele SCS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2017/12/15/black-mirror-coming-true-china-rating-affects-home-transport/| title =Black Mirror is coming true in China, where your 'rating' affects your home, transport and social circle | first = Alice | last = Vincent | date = 15 December 2017 | accessdate = 19 March 2018 | work =[[The Daily Telegraph]] }}</ref>\n\nThe proposed and existing systems have been widely compared to the episode as a whole. Specifically, it has been noted that the apartment discount Lacie hopes for is similar to how high rated people under Sesame Credit can rent cars without a deposit.<ref name=\"avclub SCS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.avclub.com/at-least-one-black-mirror-episode-is-already-coming-tru-1821315524 | title = At least one Black Mirror episode is already coming true in China | first = William | last = Hughes | date = 15 December 2017 | accessdate = 15 December 2017 | work = [[The A.V. Club]] }}</ref> Additionally, Lacie's ejection from the airport is reminiscent of the system's control over who can partake in some forms of transport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a19467976/black-mirror-social-credit-china/|title=A 'Black Mirror' Episode Is Coming to Life in China|work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|last=Bruney|first=Gabrielle|date=17 March 2018|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeries creator Charlie Brooker has commented on numerous occasions about links between the episode and the Social Credit System. He joked in an interview, \"I promise you we didn't sell the idea to the Chinese government!\" About seeing the concept of the episode come to life in the real world, Brooker said, \"It was quite trippy\".<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-on-chinas-social-credit-system-and-the-rise-of-trump | title = 'Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker on China's 'Social Credit' System and the Rise of Trump | first = Marlow | last = Stern | date = 27 October 2016 | accessdate = 15 December 2017 | work = [[The Daily Beast]] }}</ref> He comments that a key difference between China's rating system and the one in \"Nosedive\" is \"that there's a central government assessing things. Being state-controlled, it feels even more sinister\", and also points out that the Social Credit System \"sounds like an attempt to make the population behave in a particular way\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/tv/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-interview/334899|title=We got Charlie Brooker to rate real life 'Black Mirror' events|last=Sayer|first=Chris|work=[[ShortList]]|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[Adam Mosseri]], the CEO of social network [[Instagram]], said he was inspired by \"Nosedive\" to test the hiding of \"likes\" on the Instagram service starting in 2019, recognising the negative connotations that keeping the number of \"likes\" easily visible had on some users' behaviour.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/17/business/instagram-likes.html | title = This Is the Guy Who's Taking Away the Likes | first = Amy | last = Chozick | date = 17 January 2020 | accessdate = 20 January 2020 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe episode was parodied in the 2017 ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketch \"Five Stars\". It features [[Aziz Ansari]] and [[Bobby Moynihan]] desperately trying to impress each other on an [[Uber]] ride to boost each other's ratings. The sketch explicitly mentions ''Black Mirror'', with both characters saying that \"San Junipero\" is their favourite episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/recap/saturday-night-live-season-42-episode-12/|title=''Saturday Night Live'' recap: Aziz Ansari|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Holub|first=Christian|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.avclub.com/aziz-ansari-confidently-anchors-a-uniformly-strong-satu-1798190103|title=Aziz Ansari confidently anchors a uniformly strong ''Saturday Night Live''|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Perkins|first=Dennis|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n\"Nosedive\" was mostly well-received by critics. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the episode has a score of 95% based on 20 reviews, with an average score of 7.33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s03/e01|title=Black Mirror \u2013 Season 3, Episode 1 \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref> The episode garnered four-star ratings in ''The Independent'' and ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/black-mirror-season-3-episode-3-s03e03-review-release-date-spoilers-charlie-brooker-netflix-bryce-a7342551.html|title=Black Mirror season 3 episode 1 review: 'A temporary puppeteer of your thoughts'|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|date=3 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian Lee\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/sep/16/black-mirror-first-look-review-charlie-brooker|title=Black Mirror review \u2013 Charlie Brooker's splashy new series is still a sinister marvel|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016|last=Lee|first=Benjamin}}</ref> along with an A\u2212 rating in ''[[The A.V. Club]]''.<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/black-mirror-returns-please-swipe-right-244425|title=''Black Mirror'' returns, please swipe right|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Handlen|first=Zack|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> In ''[[The Mancunion]]'', the episode received 3.5 stars;<ref name=\"mancunion\">{{cite web|url=http://mancunion.com/2016/11/15/review-black-mirror-s3e01-nosedive/|title=Review: Black Mirror S3E01 \u2014 Nosedive|work=[[The Mancunion]]|last=Setranah|first=Emefa|date=15 November 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref> it was rated three stars by ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' and the ''[[Irish Independent]]''.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-season-3-nosedive-review-a-thought-provoking-pastel/|title=Black Mirror, season 3, Nosedive, review: 'a thought-provoking, pastel-coloured hell'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|last=Monahan|first=Mark|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-reviews/black-mirror-is-back-and-its-as-disturbing-as-ever-with-a-few-minor-cracks-35156063.html|title=Black Mirror is back and it's as disturbing as ever... with a few minor cracks|work=[[Irish Independent]]|last=Stacey|first=Pat|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref> Emefa Setranah of ''The Mancunion'' writes that the episode lives up to the show's reputation,<ref name=\"mancunion\"/> and ''The Guardian''{{'s}} Benjamin Lee says the episode feels fresh despite covering technology similarly to prior episodes.<ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/> Charles Bramesco writes in ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'' that it expresses the show's \"guiding theme\" with \"lucid clarity\".<ref name=\"vulture ranking\"/> ''[[TheWrap]]'' authors praise how the episode tackles society's social media obsession,<ref name=\"wrap ranking\"/> and Mat Elfring of [[GameSpot]] opines that its thought-provoking nature makes it a good choice for the season premiere.<ref name=\"gamespot ranking\"/> Matt Fowler writes for [[IGN]] that the episode is \"both fun and frustrating\" which contrasts with the \"grounded and grim\" episodes to follow.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|url=http://ign.com/articles/2016/10/19/black-mirror-season-3-review|title=BLACK MIRROR: SEASON 3 REVIEW|publisher=[[IGN]]|first=Matt|last=Fowler|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''{{'s}} Corey Atad opines that it is \"a tad too simplistic\" though \"totally engaging\".<ref name=\"esquire ranking\"/> Pat Stacey criticises the episode in the ''Irish Independent'' that it \"sets up the premise crisply, then spends far too much time labouring the point.\"<ref name=\"irish\"/>\n\nA major criticism among reviewers was the episode's predictability and repetitiveness,<ref name=\"mancunion\"/><ref name=\"comingsoon\"/> while reception to the ending was mixed. Aubrey Page on [[Collider (website)|Collider]] calls the episode \"woefully surface-level and a bit off-brand\" because of its predictability,<ref name=\"collider ranking\"/> with ''Variety''{{'s}} Andrew Wallenstein agreeing and further saying that the episode lacks a disturbing tone, though this makes it more accessible.<ref name=\"variety ranking\"/> Zack Handlen of ''The A.V. Club'' believes that the first half of \"Nosedive\" is too predictable but the second half \"[adds] depth and sincerity\".<ref name=\"avclub\"/> Tasha Robinson writes for ''[[The Verge]]'' that the episode \"can be strident and obvious\" but \"understands human nature very well\".<ref name=\"verge\"/> Some reviewers believed the episode was too long and the ending was too positive.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/><ref name=\"avclub\"/><ref name=\"forbes ranking\"/> However, ''[[Digital Spy]]''{{'s}} Alex Mullane praised the ending, because though it is \"bleak in some ways\" it is also \"a moment of sheer, fist-pumping joy\";<ref name=\"ds\"/> Jacob Hall agrees on [[/Film]], calling the ending \"simultaneously cathartic and on-the-nose\".<ref name=\"slash ranking\"/>\n\nHowever, critics had a mostly positive response to the script as a whole, with some noting comedic undertones.<ref name=\"ew ranking\"/> Robinson describes the episode as an \"exaggerated morality play about the dangers of conformity and the small pleasures of individuality\".<ref name=\"verge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/24/13379204/black-mirror-season-3-episode-1-nosedive-recap|title=Black Mirror's third season opens with a vicious take on social media|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> The script has been called \"bitingly hilarious\",<ref name=\"collider\"/> \"funny\", \"uplifting\",<ref name=\"ds\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/review/a811645/black-mirror-season-3-review-the-surprise-climax-to-nosedive-is-the-shows-biggest-twist-yet/|title=Black Mirror season 3 'Nosedive' review: this one contains the show's biggest twist yet|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Mullane|first=Alex|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref> \"moving\" and \"supremely unsettling\".<ref name=\"vulture ranking\"/> Lee approves of the script avoiding [[exposition (narrative)|exposition]].<ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/> On the other hand, ''The Telegraph''{{'s}} Mark Monahan criticises that the plot and characters do not live up to their potential.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Page feels the episode \"lacks the sadistic snap of Brooker's usual work\".<ref name=\"collider ranking\"/>\n\n[[File:Max Richter - 2015 - ATP Festival.png|thumb|alt=Max Richter performing as a pianist|[[Max Richter]]'s soundtrack for the episode was praised by reviewers.]]\n\nThe episode's visual style and Joe Wright's directing were highly commended;<ref name=\"independent\"/> the setting for the episode garnered positive reception.<ref name=\"collider\"/><ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/><ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Christian Bone of ''WhatCulture'' praises the \"distinctive pastel-coloured visual palette\"<ref name=\"what ranking\"/> and Hall compliments \"stellar production values\",<ref name=\"slash ranking\"/> while ''Forbes''{{'}} Paul Tassi calls it the \"most visually-stunning\" of the series.<ref name=\"forbes ranking\"/> Sophie Gilbert of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' praises the juxtaposition of calm visuals with narrative tension.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> Robinson notes that the aesthetics mark a difference between the characters with high and low ratings.<ref name=\"verge\"/> Adam Chitwood comments for Collider that the visual style \"keeps everything focused on the characters\", which is different to Joe Wright's typical style.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/black-mirror-season-3-review-san-junipero-nosedive/|title='Black Mirror' Season 3 Review: \"San Junipero\" and \"Nosedive\" Are a Sunny Start|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Setranah notes that Netflix's large budget is apparent in the visuals of the episode,<ref name=\"mancunion\"/> and ''The Independent'' writers suggest it is detailed enough to be revisited.<ref name=\"independent ranking\"/>\n\nMany critics praised Howard's performance,<ref name=\"avclub\"/><ref name=\"mancunion\"/><ref name=\"what ranking\"/> with Atad calling it \"delightfully unhinged\".<ref name=\"esquire ranking\"/> Additionally, Gilbert writes that Howard \"conveys Lacie's inner frustration while grinning cheerfully through it\".<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> Howard's acting ensures viewers are on Lacie's side, according to Mullane, who also compliments Eve's acting as \"excellent\".<ref name=\"ds\"/>\n\nMax Richter's musical composition for the episode was well-received. ''The Independent'' writers compliment Richter for \"blending the diegetic sounds of the app with the non-diegetic score evoking our protagonist's struggle to determine reality and fiction\",<ref name=\"independent\"/> an element which Robinson also praises.<ref name=\"verge\"/> Fowler calls the score \"very compelling\"<ref name=\"ign\"/> and Monahan describes it as \"elegantly elegiac\".<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\n===Episode ranking===\n\"Nosedive\" appears on many critics' rankings of the 19 episodes in ''Black Mirror'', from best to worst.\n{{col-begin}}{{col-2}}\n* 3rd \u2013 Charles Bramesco, ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]''<ref name=\"vulture ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/10/every-black-mirror-episode-from-worst-to-best.html | title=Every Episode of Black Mirror, Ranked From Worst to Best | author=Bramesco, Charles | date=21 October 2016 | website=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] | publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] | accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 Eric Anthony Glover, ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/every-black-mirror-episode-ranked-worst-best-93082|title=Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked, From Worst to Best|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|last=Glover|first=Eric Anthony|date=22 December 2017|accessdate=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801004027/https://www.etonline.com/every-black-mirror-episode-ranked-worst-best-93082|archive-date=2018-08-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 5th \u2013 Matt Donnelly and Tim Molloy, ''[[TheWrap]]''<ref name=\"wrap ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thewrap.com/all-13-black-mirror-episodes-ranked-from-good-to-mind-blowing-photos/14/ | title=All 13 'Black Mirror' Episodes Ranked, From Good to Mind-Blowing (Photos) |author1=Donnelly, Matt |author2=Molloy, Tim | website=[[TheWrap]] | accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 5th \u2013 Travis Clark, ''[[Business Insider]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://businessinsider.com/every-black-mirror-episode-on-netflix-ranked-from-worst-to-best-2018-5|title=All 19 episodes of 'Black Mirror,' ranked from worst to best|work=[[Business Insider]]|last=Clark|first=Travis|date=10 September 2018|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n* 6th \u2013 Morgan Jeffery, ''[[Digital Spy]]''<ref name=\"ds ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/feature/a780434/black-mirror-episodes-ranked-charlie-brooker/|title=Ranking all 13 episodes of Charlie Brooker's chilling Black Mirror|website=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|date=9 April 2017|accessdate=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806110935/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/feature/a780434/black-mirror-episodes-ranked-charlie-brooker/|archive-date=2018-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n* 8th \u2013 Aubrey Page, ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''<ref name=\"collider ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://collider.com/black-mirror-episodes-ranked | title=Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked From Worst to Best | date=28 October 2016 | author=Page, Aubrey | publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] | accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 9th \u2013 James Hibberd, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref name=\"ew ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://ew.com/gallery/black-mirror-episodes-ranked/no-9-nosedive-season-3 | title='Black Mirror': We Rank All 19 Episodes | author=Hibberd, James | date=23 October 2016 | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n* 13th \u2013 Corey Atad, ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''<ref name=\"esquire ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a49919/black-mirror-episodes-ranked/ | title=Every Episode of Black Mirror, Ranked | date=24 October 2016 | author=Atad, Corey | website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] | publisher = [[Hearst Communications]] | accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 13th \u2013 Steve Greene, Hanh Nguyen and Liz Shannon Miller, [[IndieWire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/11/best-black-mirror-episodes-worst-netflix-ranked-1201897973/|title=Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked, From Worst to Best|last1=Greene|first1=Steve|last2=Nguyen|first2=Hanh|last3=Miller|first3=Liz Shannon|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|date=24 November 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\nInstead of by quality, Proma Khosla of [[Mashable]] ranked each episode by tone, concluding that \"Nosedive\" is the 15th most pessimistic of the 19 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/01/05/black-mirror-pessimism-ranking-dread|title=Every 'Black Mirror' episode ever, ranked by overall dread|publisher=[[Mashable]]|last=Khosla|first=Proma|date=5 January 2018|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther critics ranked the 13 episodes in ''Black Mirror''{{'}}s first three series.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* 3rd \u2013 Christian Bone, ''WhatCulture''<ref name=\"what ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/tv/black-mirror-ranking-every-episode-from-worst-to-best?page=12|title=Black Mirror: Ranking Every Episode From Worst To Best|work=WhatCulture|last=Bone|first=Christian|date=4 November 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 6th \u2013 Adam David, [[CNN Philippines]]<ref name=\"cnn ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/life/entertainment/television/2016/10/24/black-mirror-ranked-episodes.html|title=How to watch all 'Black Mirror' episodes, from worst to best|last=David|first=Adam|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 7th \u2013 Mat Elfring, [[GameSpot]]<ref name=\"gamespot ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/gallery/black-mirror-every-episode-ranked-from-good-to-bes/2900-956/10/ | title=Black Mirror: Every Episode Ranked From Good to Best | author=Elfring, Mat | date=28 October 2016 | publisher=[[GameSpot]] | accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n* 8th \u2013 Ed Power, ''The Telegraph''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-every-episode-ranked-rated/|title=Black Mirror: every episode ranked and rated|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|last=Power|first=Ed|date=28 December 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n* 9th \u2013 Jacob Hall, [[/Film]]<ref name=\"slash ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/black-mirror-episode-ranking/3/|title=Through a Touchscreen Darkly: Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked|publisher=[[/Film]]|last=Hall|first=Jacob|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 9th (of the Top Ten) \u2013 Brendan Doyle, [[Comingsoon.net]]<ref name=\"comingsoon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/908789-the-top-ten-black-mirror-episodes|title=The Top Ten Black Mirror Episodes|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|last=Doyle|first=Brendan|date=17 December 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 10th \u2013 Andrew Wallenstein, ''Variety''<ref name=\"variety ranking\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/black-mirror-episodes-rank-binge-guide-netflix-1201894706/|title='Black Mirror' Episodes Ranked: Spoiler-Free Guide to Seasons 1\u20133|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Wallenstein|first=Andrew|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\nSome critics ranked the six episodes from series three of ''Black Mirror'' in order of quality.\n* 2nd \u2013 Jacob Stolworthy and Christopher Hooton, ''The Independent''<ref name=\"independent ranking\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-episodes-1-6-netflix-ranked-a7373321.html|title=Black Mirror review: The season 3 episodes, ranked|work=[[The Independent]]|last1=Stolworthy|first1=Jacob|last2=Hooton|first2=Christopher|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 Paul Tassi, ''[[Forbes]]''<ref name=\"forbes ranking\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2016/10/25/ranking-black-mirror-season-3s-episodes-from-worst-to-best/|title=Ranking 'Black Mirror' Season 3's Episodes From Worst To Best|work=[[Forbes]]|last=Tassi|first=Paul|date=25 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 Liam Hoofe, ''Flickering Myth''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2016/10/ranking-black-mirror-season-3-episodes-from-worst-to-best/2/|title=Ranking Black Mirror Season 3 Episodes from Worst to Best|work=Flickering Myth|last=Hoofe|first=Liam|date=29 October 2016|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{{See also|Black Mirror#Accolades}}\n\"Nosedive\" was nominated for several awards in 2017; the third season of ''Black Mirror'' also received several other nominations and awards.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Award nominations for \"Nosedive\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipients\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n| [[2017 British Academy Television Craft Awards|BAFTA Television Craft Awards]]\n| Best Photography and Lighting \u2013 Fiction\n| [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/television/craft-awards/tv-craft-awards-2017#photography--lighting-fiction---rillington-place|title=Television Craft Awards Winners 2017|publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] (BAFTA)|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[23rd Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Television Movie or Miniseries]]\n|[[Bryce Dallas Howard]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/2017-sag-awards-nominations-nominees-list-1201941897/|title=SAG Award Nominations: Complete List|publisher=[[SAG-AFTRA|Screen Actors Guild\u2010American Federation of Television and Radio Artists]] (SAG-AFTRA)|first=Seth|last=Kelley|date=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Art Directors Guild Awards 2016|Art Directors Guild Awards]]\n| Excellence in Production Design for a Television Movie or Limited Series\n| Joel Collins, James Foster and Nicholas Palmer <br><small>(Also nominated for \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\" and \"[[San Junipero]]\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=Art Directors Guild Awards Nominations: 'Rogue One', 'Game Of Thrones' & More|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/art-directors-guild-nominations-2017-full-list-1201878962/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[48th NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Awards]]\n| Outstanding Writing in a Motion Picture \u2013 Television\n| [[Rashida Jones]] and [[Michael Schur]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2017-naacp-image-award-winners-televised-966471/item/outstanding-literary-work-youth-teens-955892 |title=Hidden Figures, Loving, and Queen of Katwe nominated |last2=Lewis  |first2=Hilary | last1=Washington |first1=Arlene |date=10 February 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[69th Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or Movie]]\n| [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2017/outstanding-cinematography-for-a-miniseries-or-movie|title=69th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Board game==\nBased on the episode, the board game ''Nosedive'' was produced by [[Asmodee]]. Released on 25 November 2018, the game requires between three and six players and is designed to last for roughly 45 minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/15/18097545/black-mirror-nosedive-board-game-asmodee | title = Black Mirror's nightmarish social media episode is now a board game | first = Michael | last = McWhertor | date = 15 November 2018 | accessdate = 1 July 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> A mobile app, available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] or [[iOS]], is used to play the game; it initially assigns each player a Social Score. In the initial Lifestyle phase, players draw cards which have ratings between one and five stars, such as the one star card \"A six-minute lunch break\". They tactically assign them to stacks and then each player selects a stack. In the Experience phase, players assign each other experiences such as \"Receiving an anonymous hate cake\" and each player then rates their received experiences from one to five stars. The app then adjusts each player's Social Score based on these ratings. At the end of the game, players earn points from the Lifestyle cards they own which have star ratings less than or equal to their Social Score.<ref name=\"Verge board game\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/8/18120393/black-mirror-nosedive-card-app-game-asmodee-review|title=The Black Mirror card game isn't soul-crushing enough to reflect the show|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=8 December 2018|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nTasha Robinson of ''[[The Verge]]'' criticised the game's mechanics as feeling arbitrary, as users' Social Scores are mostly determined by random factors. However, Robinson praised the app's design, the game's pastel aesthetics and the humour of the Experience cards, which can lead to interesting discussion.<ref name=\"Verge board game\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb episode|5497778|Nosedive}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/shows/black-mirror/nosedive-3425428/ \"Nosedive\"] at [[TV.com]]\n\n{{Black Mirror}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Nosedive (''Black Mirror'')}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nosedive}}\n[[Category:2016 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Augmented reality in fiction]]\n[[Category:Black Mirror episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about social media]]\n[[Category:Social reputation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Netflix original television series episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = Nosedive\n| series = [[Black Mirror]]\n| image = [[File:Black Mirror - Nosedive.jpg|280px]]\n| caption = Lacie ([[Bryce Dallas Howard]]) gives a rating using her phone. The episode's pastel colours distinguish it from most ''Black Mirror'' episodes.\n| series_no = 3\n| episode = 1\n| story = [[Charlie Brooker]]\n| teleplay = [[Michael Schur]]<br> [[Rashida Jones]]\n| director = [[Joe Wright]]\n| photographer = [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| length = 63 minutes\n| release_date = {{Start date|df=yes|2016|10|21}}\n| guests =\n* [[Bryce Dallas Howard]] as Lacie Pound\n* [[Alice Eve]] as Naomi Blestow\n* [[Cherry Jones]] as Susan\n* [[James Norton (actor)|James Norton]] as Ryan Pound\n* [[Alan Ritchson]] as Paul\n* [[Daisy Haggard]] as Bets\n* [[Susannah Fielding]] as Carol\n* [[Michaela Coel]] as Airline Stewardess\n* [[Kadiff Kirwan]] as Chester\n* [[Sope Dirisu|\u1e62\u1ecdp\u1eb9\u0301 D\u00ecr\u00eds\u00f9]] as Man in Jail\n* Andrew Roux as Electro Station Attendant\n| prev = [[White Christmas (Black Mirror)|White Christmas]]\n| next = [[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\n| episode_list = List of Black Mirror episodes\n}}\n\n\"'''Nosedive'''\" is the first episode in the third series of the British science fiction [[anthology series]] ''[[Black Mirror]]''. [[Michael Schur]] and [[Rashida Jones]] wrote the teleplay for the episode, based on a story by series creator and co-showrunner [[Charlie Brooker]], while [[Joe Wright]] acted as director. It premiered on [[Netflix]] on 21 October 2016, alongside the rest of the third series.\n\nThe episode is set in a world where people can rate each other from one to five stars for every interaction they have, which can impact their [[socioeconomic status]]. Lacie ([[Bryce Dallas Howard]]) is a young woman overly obsessed with her ratings; she finds an opportunity to elevate her ratings greatly and move into a more luxurious residence after being chosen by her popular childhood friend ([[Alice Eve]]) as the maid of honour for her wedding. Her obsession leads to several mishaps on her journey to the wedding that culminate in a rapid reduction in her ratings.\n\nUnder Netflix, the episode was given a much larger budget than the previous episodes of the programme, when it had been under [[Channel 4]]. Brooker wrote an outline for the episode, then Schur wrote the former half of the episode and Jones wrote the latter. Production was undertaken in a manner similar to a short film; \"Nosedive\" was filmed in [[South Africa]], with [[Seamus McGarvey]] as [[director of photography]] and Joel Collins and James Foster as the [[production designers]]. The tone of the episode is less bleak and more comedic than other ''Black Mirror'' episodes, with the ending significantly more positive than in episodes of the programme's prior two series.\n\nThe episode received mainly positive reviews and is middling in critics' lists of ''Black Mirror'' episodes, qualitatively. The pastel visual aesthetics were widely praised, along with [[Max Richter]]'s soundtrack and Howard's performance. A criticism from several reviewers was the episode's predictability and ending, though the script and comedic undertones were praised by some. Many critics noted the similarity of the episode to real world app [[Peeple (mobile application)|Peeple]] and China's upcoming [[Social Credit System]], along with fictional works about social media with themes of gender and obsession with image. The episode was nominated for several awards, including a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] nomination for Howard and a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for McGarvey. A board game ''Nosedive'', based on the episode, was released in 2018.\n\n==Plot==\nSociety has embraced a technology wherein everyone shares their daily activities through eye implants and mobile devices and rates their interactions with others on a scale of one to five stars, cumulatively affecting everyone's [[socioeconomic status]].\n\nLacie Pound ([[Bryce Dallas Howard]]) seeks to raise her 4.2 rating to 4.5 for a discount on a luxury apartment; however, despite her attempts to be an outgoing and pleasant socialite, her rating has plateaued. Lacie talks to a consultant who suggests gaining favour from very highly-rated people. Lacie uploads a photograph of Mr. Rags, a ragdoll that she and her childhood friend Naomi ([[Alice Eve]]) made together. Naomi, who is currently rated 4.8, rates the photo five stars and calls Lacie, saying that she is engaged and inviting Lacie to deliver a speech as the maid of honour. Lacie agrees and commits on the apartment, anticipating many high ratings from the guests.\n\nOn the day of her flight, several mishaps cause people to rate Lacie negatively, dropping her rating below 4.2. At the airport, her flight is cancelled and she cannot buy a seat with her current rating. When Lacie causes a scene, security penalizes her by subtracting a full point for 24 hours. Because of her low rating, Lacie can only rent an older car to drive to the wedding, which she cannot recharge when it runs out of power. She is forced to hitchhike with Susan ([[Cherry Jones]]), a truck driver rated below 2.0. Susan tells Lacie that she used to care about her rating until her late husband was passed over for vital cancer treatment because their scores were deemed not high enough; she says she feels much freer without obsessing over ratings.\n\nThe next day, while Lacie is en route to the wedding, Naomi tells her to not come, as her severely reduced rating will negatively impact Naomi's own ratings. Enraged, Lacie reaches the wedding and sneaks in during the reception. She grabs the microphone and starts giving the speech she had written but becomes more and more upset, finally grabbing a knife and threatening to behead Mr. Rags. The guests rate Lacie negatively, causing her rating to fall below one star. Security arrives and arrests Lacie. She is taken to prison, and the technology supporting the rating system is removed from her eyes. She and the man in the cell opposite hers ([[Sope Dirisu]]) realise they can now speak without worrying about being rated, and gleefully hurl insults at each other.\n\n==Production==\n{{external media\n|video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jDiYGjp5iFg Black Mirror \u2013 Season 3]<br>The trailer for series three of ''Black Mirror''.\n|video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R32qWdOWrTo Black Mirror \u2013 Nosedive Featurette]<br>Brief commentary by Charlie Brooker and Bryce Dallas Howard.\n}}\n\"Nosedive\" is the first episode of the third series of ''Black Mirror''; all six episodes in this series were released on Netflix simultaneously on 21 October 2016. Brooker says it was selected to be the season premiere \"partly to slightly ease people in\",<ref name=\"worst year ever\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-charlie-brooker-interview-release-date-joe-wright-nosedive-shut-up-and-dance-a7372841.html|title=Black Mirror co-creator Charlie Brooker: 'I'm loath to say this is the worst year ever because the next is coming'|date=21 October 2016|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> at Netflix's recommendation.<ref name=\"ibm\"/> Alongside \"[[San Junipero]]\", \"Nosedive\" was first shown in 2016 ahead of its Netflix release at the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"collider\"/> Two days prior to the series' release on Netflix, Brooker hinted that \"Nosedive\" is \"a pastel, playful satire about modern insecurity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/black-mirror/44587/black-mirror-series-3-interview-charlie-brooker-and-annabel-jones|title=Black Mirror series 3 interview: Charlie Brooker and Annabel Jones|work=Den of Geek!|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|last=Mellor|first=Louisa|date=19 October 2016|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhilst series one and two of ''Black Mirror'' were shown on [[Channel 4]] in the UK, in September 2015 Netflix commissioned the series for 12 episodes (split into two series of six episodes),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/netflix-black-mirror-new-episodes-1201602037/|title=Netflix Picks Up 'Black Mirror' for 12 New Episodes|first=Debra |last=Birnbaum|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=25 September 2016|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> and in March 2016 it outbid Channel 4 for the rights to distributing the third series, with a bid of $40 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/mar/29/netflix-channel-4-charlie-brooker-black-mirror |title=Netflix deals Channel 4 knockout blow over Charlie Brooker's Black Mirror |first=John |last=Plunkett |date=29 March 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> Due to its move to Netflix, the show had a larger budget than in previous series,<ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/> which one critic suggests is responsible for the \"impressive line-up\" that was noted by many reviewers.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Another critic called this episode the show's \"most ambitious yet\";<ref name=\"Independent Community\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/black-mirror-season-3-episode-nosedive-community-meow-meow-beanz-a7376651.html|title=Black Mirror season 3 episode 'Nosedive' is very similar to Community episode 'App Development and Condiments'|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> due to its larger episode order, series 3 was also able to vary its genre and tone more than previous series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/21/arts/television/review-black-mirror-finds-terror-and-soul-in-the-machine.html|title=Review: 'Black Mirror' Finds Terror, and Soul, in the Machine|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> One reviewer also noted that \"Nosedive\" contained \"only American characters\".<ref name=\"collider\"/>\n\nIn November 2016, to tie in with the episode, Netflix released a tongue-in-cheek app called Rate Me. The app allows users to rate people, by their [[Twitter]] handle, and view their own rating and the ratings of others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/rate-me-nosedive-black-mirror-netflix|title=Black Mirror's horrific people-rating app is now a reality. Sort of|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|last=Temperton|first=James|date=10 November 2016|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conception and writing===\n{{multiple image|align=left|total_width=250|image1=Rashida Jones at 2017 MIFF.jpg|height1=3000|width1=2151|image2=Michael Schur 2012 (cropped).jpg|height2=812|width2=530|footer=[[Rashida Jones]] and [[Michael Schur]], who co-wrote the script for \"Nosedive\".}}\nThe episode is based on an idea by series creator [[Charlie Brooker]] for a movie; he and executive producer [[Annabel Jones]] pitched the idea to several movie companies in the United States after the first series of ''Black Mirror'', but it was not commissioned.<ref name=\"ibm\">{{cite book | title = Inside Black Mirror | date = November 2018 | first1 = Charlie | last1 = Brooker | first2 = Annabel | last2 = Jones | first3 = Jason | last3 = Arnopp | chapter = Nosedive | isbn = 9781984823489 | publisher = [[Crown Publishing Group]] | place = New York City }}</ref> The original idea was of a comedy similar to ''[[Brewster's Millions]]'', focused on a high status person trying to reduce their ranking in 24 hours.<ref name=\"ibm\"/><ref name=\"Decider\"/> Later, Brooker wrote either a three<ref name=\"ew interview\"/> or four<ref name=\"avclub interview\"/> page outline for the episode, wanting it to be \"comedic, darkly\".<ref name=\"ew interview\"/> This version took inspiration from 1987 film ''[[Planes, Trains and Automobiles]]'', in which the character is on a journey\u2014for \"Nosedive\", this was initially a character travelling to an important work presentation.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>\n\n[[Rashida Jones]] and [[Michael Schur]] wrote the episode. Known for comedy and sitcoms, the pair had previously worked together on many shows, including ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'', but had never written anything together before \"Nosedive\".<ref name=\"avclub interview\"/> A fan of Brooker's works, Rashida Jones had been in contact with him for a few years beforehand and after the programme's move to Netflix, he suggested that she could write an episode. Schur was also a fan of ''Black Mirror'' and Rashida Jones suggested that they could co-write the episode. With Jones and Schur on board, the main character changed from someone focused on playing the ratings system to a people-pleaser, the work presentation was changed to a wedding and the idea of Lacie having a childhood talisman was introduced. Lacie's brother was originally an ex-boyfriend.<ref name=\"ibm\"/> Schur wrote the first half of the episode (up to Lacie beginning her travel in a rented car), while Rashida Jones wrote the second half, and the two then combined their scripts.<ref name=\"avclub interview\"/> In the initial draft, the episode ended with Lacie's work presentation going viral and her achieving fame. The final version of the ending showed Lacie in a jail cell, the rating device removed from her, allowing her to find freedom. An unused idea was that of rage rooms, where characters would go to destroy things to let out their anger.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>\n\nIn 2016, Schur had an account on [[Twitter]] but not [[Facebook]] or [[Instagram]], as \"there's a bunch of strangers talking shit about you in there\", and Jones expressed a similarly negative attitude, stating \"I do have very strong, very conflicted feelings about rating systems and social media.\"<ref name=\"avclub interview\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.avclub.com/rashida-jones-and-michael-schur-talk-about-bringing-fun-1798254169|title=Rashida Jones and Michael Schur talk about bringing funny to ''Black Mirror''|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Zuckerman|first=Esther|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> Brooker notes that \"you are rewarded for having a more extreme opinion\" on social media; in the episode, as on the internet, almost all ratings given are either one or five stars.<ref name=\"slate interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2016/10/21/the_stars_and_writers_of_black_mirror_on_the_disturbing_new_season.html|title=''Black Mirror''{{'}}s Stars and Writers on How They Made the Most Disturbing Season Yet|last=Adams|first=Sam|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> Similarly, Schur opines that social media causes people to exaggerate their behaviour, particularly their rudeness.<ref name=\"time\"/> Jones believes that the episode, as with all ''Black Mirror'' episodes, \"pushes you into the near future\", while Schur considers it to be more of a \"parallel reality\". Brooker has described the episode as \"like a cross between ''[[Pleasantville (film)|Pleasantville]]'' and ''[[The Truman Show]]''\".<ref name=\"ew interview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/23/black-mirror-postmortem-interview-season-3|title=Black Mirror postmortem: Showrunner talks season 3 twists|date=21 October 2016|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref> Jones says the idea that \"women are taught to be liked, and men are taught to be powerful\", credited to [[Sheryl Sandberg]], is relevant to the episode, with Schur agreeing that Lacie's gender is important to the story,<ref name=\"slate interview\"/> though Schur notes that edited images on social media are causing negative [[body image]] issues for men as well.<ref name=\"time\">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4538883/black-mirror-netflix-rashida-jones-mike-schur/|title=Rashida Jones and Mike Schur's ''Black Mirror'' Episode Will Make You Rethink How You Use Social Media|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|last=Dockterman|first=Eliana|date=20 October 2016|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Joe Wright by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Joe Wright]], the episode's director]]\nThe episode was the third in series three to be filmed.<ref name=\"ibm\"/> [[Joe Wright]] directed the episode, [[Seamus McGarvey]] was [[director of photography]] and the production designers, working for [[VFX]] company Painting Practice, were Joel Collins<ref name=\"creative review\"/> and James Foster.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/awards/joe-wright-relished-polyester-fabric-black-mirror-after-period-films-1202460842/|title=Joe Wright Relished the Chance to Go Polyester in 'Black Mirror'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Tobias|first=Scott|date=12 June 2017|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref> The episode was shot in four weeks<ref name=\"variety\"/> in [[Knysna]], [[South Africa]],<ref name=\"ibm\"/> a coastal town five hours (by car) from [[Cape Town]] chosen as it felt like an American coastal town.<ref name=\"creative review\"/><ref name=\"ibm\"/> Series three episode \"[[San Junipero]]\" was also filmed in South Africa.<ref name=\"creative review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.creativereview.co.uk/designing-black-mirror-interview-production-designer-joel-collins/|title=Black Mirror production designer Joel Collins on bringing Charlie Brooker's dystopian visions to life|work=[[Creative Review]]|last=Steven|first=Rachael|url-access=registration|date=16 November 2016|accessdate=5 January 2018}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', McGarvey noted that the episode was shot in [[4K resolution]] at the request of Netflix; he said the [[colour scheme]] was a mixture of [[wikt:duck-egg blue|duck-egg blue]], \"peppermint green\" and \"strange [[peach (color)|peach colors]]\", and that props and \"even the drinks people are drinking\" were chosen with care to create a \"sickly pastel feel\".<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/awards/emmys-black-mirror-seamus-mcgarvey-interview-1202520496/|title='Black Mirror' DP Seamus McGarvey Talks About Finding the 'Photographic Heart' of 'Nosedive'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|date=16 August 2017|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref> Wright said that he made almost no changes to the script's dialogue.<ref name=\"nofilmschool\">{{cite podcast|url=https://nofilmschool.com/2017/07/black-mirror-joe-wright-and-owen-harris|title='Black Mirror': How Directors Joe Wright and Owen Harris Built Dystopian Worlds That Look Like Our Own [PODCAST]|website=No Film School|last=Fusco|first=Jon|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref> Brooker has said that Wright's pastel treatment was a \"very strong visual idea that we had not foreseen\".<ref name=\"independent podcast\">{{cite podcast|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/charlie-brooker-interview-black-mirror-season-4-twitter-episode-writer-westworld-screenwriting-a8090086.html|title=Charlie Brooker interview: Black Mirror creator on season 4, plot option paralysis and being on Twitter less|website=[[The Independent]]|last=Hooton|first=Christopher|date=4 December 2017|accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrooker pointed out that directors of ''Black Mirror'' episodes (in this case, Wright) have more \"power\" than in serialised television shows, as \"it is like making a short film\", and he said that Wright had \"been feeling quite bruised after doing ''[[Pan (2015 film)|Pan]]'', and [''Black Mirror''] was a good thing for him to get his teeth into which wasn't the full five-year commitment of a movie\".<ref name=\"worst year ever\"/> McGarvey had previously worked with Wright.<ref name=\"variety\"/> Watching [[dailies|rushes]] from the filming, Brooker was initially sceptical about Wright's saccharine style, but began to understand it as the filming progressed and the music was added.<ref name=\"independent podcast\"/> The scenes in which Lacie is driving utilise a [[computer-generated imagery|computer-generated]] landscape designed by Dan May, the episode's art director.<ref name=\"creative review\"/> She was initially planned to drive through multiple landscapes such as a desert, but this was changed for budget reasons.<ref name=\"ibm\"/>\n\nBryce Dallas Howard plays Lacie, the episode's main character. She was suggested by Wright, who auditioned her a decade previously for ''[[Atonement (film)|Atonement]]''.<ref name=\"nofilmschool\"/> Howard gained {{convert|30|lb|kg}} for the role, saying in an interview with ''[[Marie Claire]]'' that body shaming is a \"huge part of the subtext of the story\".<ref name=\"marie claire\"/> She chose a laugh for Lacie which mixed \"fear\", \"disingenuousness\" and \"depression\".<ref name=\"ibm\"/> Howard first joined social media during Thanksgiving 2015 and was approached with the [[film treatment|treatment]] of the episode a fortnight later, in December 2015.<ref name=\"marie claire\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/news/a23270/bryce-dallas-howard-black-mirror-interview/|title=Bryce Dallas Howard on Body Image, Social Media, and Gaining 30 Pounds for 'Black Mirror'|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|work=[[Marie Claire]]|date=26 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"cosmopolitan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/tv/a7666694/black-mirror-bryce-dallas-howard-alice-eve-nosedive-interview/|title=Black Mirror Stars on the Terrifying Episode That May Make You Delete Your Instagram|work=[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|last=Dibdin|first=Emma|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nChosen by Wright to compose the episode's soundtrack,<ref name=\"independent podcast\"/> [[Max Richter]] is a self-described \"conservatoire, university-trained classical composer\".<ref name=\"Richter Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/11/max-richter-interview-black-mirror-the-leftovers-miss-sloane/506033/|title=Max Richter's Soundtrack to Dystopia|work=[[The Atlantic]]|last=Gilbert|first=Sophie|date=1 November 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> Richter first met the director, Joe Wright, in London before the shooting of the episode had been completed and began coming up with ideas for the score. Richter aimed to \"support\" the episode's display of \"incredible anxiety hovering beneath this smiley surface ... while at the same time not flattening out the emotionality of it\", commenting in an interview that Wright's camerawork had a \"dream-like quality\" and that Brooker's \"story was fantastic\".<ref name=\"Richter Fact\">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2016/10/27/max-richter-soundtrack-black-mirror-nosedive/|title=Black Mirror composer Max Richter on soundtracking society's social media meltdown|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|last=Warwick|first=Oli|date=27 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> In another interview, Richter said he was aiming for the episode to have \"warmth and a fairytale quality throughout\" with \"darkness underneath it\", and notes that his composition was based on \"the sentiment and the emotional trajectory of the characters\". Richter also composed the sound effects which play when one character rates another, and incorporated these sounds into the score itself.<ref name=\"Richter Atlantic\"/>\n\n==Analysis==\nSeveral critics compared the episode to a 2014 episode of ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'', \"[[App Development and Condiments]]\", which features an app where users assign each other \"Meow Meow Beenz\" ratings on a scale from one to five; Jack Shepherd of ''[[The Independent]]'' notes that both episodes \"critically [analyse] people's obsession with stature on social media platforms with rating systems\".<ref name=\"Independent Community\"/> Other reviewers compared \"Nosedive\" to the [[mobile application]] [[Peeple (mobile application)|Peeple]],<ref name=\"Atlantic\">{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Sophie|title='Black Mirror' Is Back: 'Nosedive' Is a Sharp Satire About Social Media|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/10/black-mirror-nosedive-review-season-three-netflix/504668/|accessdate=22 October 2016|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=21 October 2016}}</ref> in which users could rate one another, that garnered immediate backlash upon its release.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/><ref name=\"Decider\"/> Brooker said in an interview that he was not aware of the ''Community'' episode when he came up with the idea for \"Nosedive\", but that he did see advertising for Peeple during pre-production, initially thinking it would turn out to be marketing for a comedy show, and he considered whether or not they should still produce the episode.<ref name=\"Decider\">{{cite web|url=http://decider.com/2016/10/27/black-mirror-nosedive-did-not-steal-from-community-interview/|title=Did 'Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker Know About That 'Community' Episode When He Made \"Nosedive\"?|last=Cobb|first=Kayla|work=Decider|publisher=[[New York Post]]|date=27 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> The episode has also been compared to the 2003 novel ''[[Down and Out in the Magic Kingdom]]'', as each work explores a link between social approval and power.<ref name=\"verge\"/>\n\nManuel Betancourt of ''[[Pacific Standard]]'' explains how \"Nosedive\" fits with other portrayals of social media in television and film, comparing it to 2017 films ''[[The Circle (2017 film)|The Circle]]'' and ''[[Ingrid Goes West]]'', which both explore negative aspects of social media. Betancourt says that historically, women have been portrayed as victims of technology, a pattern which these works fit. For instance, Ingrid and Lacie are both obsessed with coming across as perfect online. In contrast, male characters are traditionally the voice of reason: in these works, Lacie's brother Ryan, Mercer (''The Circle'') and Taylor's husband (''Ingrid Goes West'') serve this purpose.<ref name=\"pacific\"/> Furthermore, the androgyny of \"Nosedive\" character Susan is linked to her disdain for social media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailytitan.com/2017/04/female-gaze-black-mirror-explores-gendered-expectations-social-media/|title=The Female Gaze: 'Black Mirror' explores the gendered expectations of social media|work=[[The Daily Titan]]|last=Casas|first=Darlene|date=11 April 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref> Betancourt writes that these characterisations do not accord with research on how men and women use technology, where some studies report that men have more emotional investment in positive feedback on social media. However, \"Nosedive\" shows people of all genders placing importance in social media, leading Betancourt to call it \"perhaps the most keen-eyed critique [...] of recent titles\".<ref name=\"pacific\">{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/social-justice/why-are-so-many-ladies-insta-fiends-in-movies|title=Why Does Hollywood Tell So Many Stories About Women Obsessed With Social Media?|work=[[Pacific Magazine]]|last=Betancourt|first=Manuel|date=11 August 2017|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nA ''[[Business Insider]]'' article by Erin Brodwin notes that the episode shows Lacie fall victim to the [[hedonic treadmill]]. Despite momentary happiness when receiving a high rating, Lacie is \"lonely and unsatisfied\". Brodwin points out that scientific studies concur with Lacie's experience, because there is no correlation between using social media and being happy in the long-term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/psychology-black-mirror-nosedive-social-media-2016-10|title=What psychology actually says about the tragically social-media obsessed society in 'Black Mirror'|work=[[Business Insider]]|last=Brodwin|first=Erin|date=27 October 2016|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nCritics have also noted the inclusion of [[Easter egg (media)|Easter eggs]] within ''Black Mirror''&nbsp;\u2013 small details referring to other episodes. In \"Nosedive\", there is a frame where a social media post from Michael Callow reads, \"Just got thrown out of the zoo again :(\", a joke based on Callow having intercourse with a pig in \"[[The National Anthem (Black Mirror)|The National Anthem]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/22898-black-mirror-season-3-easter-eggs|title=Every Single 'Black Mirror' Season 3 Easter Egg|work=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]]|last=Hutchinson|first=Sean|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> Brooker has described this Easter egg as his favourite in series three.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://decider.com/2016/11/03/netflix-black-mirror-charlie-brooker-annabel-jones-interview/|title='Black Mirror' Creators Talk About Season Three's Easter Eggs And What Your Favorite Episode Says About You|last=Cobb|first=Kayla|work=Decider|publisher=[[New York Post]]|date=3 November 2016|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> Another reference to that episode is the fictional show ''Sea of Tranquility''; in \"The National Anthem\", a special effects expert mentions having worked on the show, while in \"Nosedive\", Lacie hitchhikes with fans of the show. Additionally, in \"[[Hated in the Nation]]\", a news ticker contains the term \"Reputelligent\", which is the name of the company that Lacie consults for advice about her rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screencrush.com/black-mirror-easter-eggs-theory/|title=24 Easter Eggs From All Three Seasons of 'Black Mirror', Plus a Timeline Connecting Every Episode|work=ScreenCrush|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|last=Whitney|first=Erin Oliver|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Comparisons to Social Credit System===\n\"Nosedive\" has been widely compared to China's [[Social Credit System]], a governmental initiative planned for testing in 2020,<ref name=\"nme SCS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/tv/black-mirrors-nosedive-episode-become-reality-china-2263309|title=Black Mirror's 'Nosedive' episode is about to become reality in China|last=Connick|first=Tom|work=[[NME]]|date=14 March 2018|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> and existing Chinese reputation systems such as [[Sesame Credit]].<ref name=\"dog SCS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/uk/tv/black-mirror/45041/how-black-mirror-series-3-is-eerily-coming-true|title=How Black Mirror series 3 is eerily coming true|work=[[Den of Geek!]]|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|last=Leane|first=Rob|date=3 November 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BM&Philosophy\">{{Citation|last=Urue\u00f1a|first=Sergio|title=Nosedive and the Anxieties of Social Media|date=2019|work=Black Mirror and Philosophy|pages=81\u201391|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd|language=en|doi=10.1002/9781119578291.ch8|isbn=978-1-119-57829-1|last2=Melikyan|first2=Nonna}}</ref> In November 2016, the Facebook page for ''Black Mirror'' shared an article in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' about the Social Credit System.{{efn|group=note|The article shared was the following: {{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20/1cd0dd9c-9516-11e6-ae9d-0030ac1899cd_story.html|title=China's plan to organize its society relies on 'big data' to rate everyone|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=22 October 2016}}}} The system would assign each citizen a score determining decisions such as \"whether you can borrow money\" or \"get your children into the best schools\", and that actions such as \"defaulting on a loan\" or \"criticizing the ruling party\" would lead to a lower score. The existing Sesame Credit system, which assigns users scores between 350 and 950,<ref name=\"tele SCS\"/> already allowed some people with high scores to rent vehicles without a deposit, or pay to skip hospital queues.<ref name=\"dog SCS\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinas-plan-to-organize-its-whole-society-around-big-data-a-rating-for-everyone/2016/10/20|title=China's plan to organize its society relies on 'big data' to rate everyone|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Denyer|first=Simon|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, a person's score in Sesame Credit is dependent on the scores of the people in their social circle.<ref name=\"tele SCS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/2017/12/15/black-mirror-coming-true-china-rating-affects-home-transport/| title =Black Mirror is coming true in China, where your 'rating' affects your home, transport and social circle | first = Alice | last = Vincent | date = 15 December 2017 | accessdate = 19 March 2018 | work =[[The Daily Telegraph]] }}</ref>\n\nThe proposed and existing systems have been widely compared to the episode as a whole. Specifically, it has been noted that the apartment discount Lacie hopes for is similar to how high rated people under Sesame Credit can rent cars without a deposit.<ref name=\"avclub SCS\">{{cite web | url = https://www.avclub.com/at-least-one-black-mirror-episode-is-already-coming-tru-1821315524 | title = At least one Black Mirror episode is already coming true in China | first = William | last = Hughes | date = 15 December 2017 | accessdate = 15 December 2017 | work = [[The A.V. Club]] }}</ref> Additionally, Lacie's ejection from the airport is reminiscent of the system's control over who can partake in some forms of transport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a19467976/black-mirror-social-credit-china/|title=A 'Black Mirror' Episode Is Coming to Life in China|work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|last=Bruney|first=Gabrielle|date=17 March 2018|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeries creator Charlie Brooker has commented on numerous occasions about links between the episode and the Social Credit System. He joked in an interview, \"I promise you we didn't sell the idea to the Chinese government!\" About seeing the concept of the episode come to life in the real world, Brooker said, \"It was quite trippy\".<ref>{{cite web | url =  https://www.thedailybeast.com/black-mirror-creator-charlie-brooker-on-chinas-social-credit-system-and-the-rise-of-trump | title = 'Black Mirror' Creator Charlie Brooker on China's 'Social Credit' System and the Rise of Trump | first = Marlow | last = Stern | date = 27 October 2016 | accessdate = 15 December 2017 | work = [[The Daily Beast]] }}</ref> He comments that a key difference between China's rating system and the one in \"Nosedive\" is \"that there's a central government assessing things. Being state-controlled, it feels even more sinister\", and also points out that the Social Credit System \"sounds like an attempt to make the population behave in a particular way\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/tv/black-mirror-charlie-brooker-interview/334899|title=We got Charlie Brooker to rate real life 'Black Mirror' events|last=Sayer|first=Chris|work=[[ShortList]]|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[Adam Mosseri]], the CEO of social network [[Instagram]], said he was inspired by \"Nosedive\" to test the hiding of \"likes\" on the Instagram service starting in 2019, recognising the negative connotations that keeping the number of \"likes\" easily visible had on some users' behaviour.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/17/business/instagram-likes.html | title = This Is the Guy Who's Taking Away the Likes | first = Amy | last = Chozick | date = 17 January 2020 | accessdate = 20 January 2020 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe episode was parodied in the 2017 ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketch \"Five Stars\". It features [[Aziz Ansari]] and [[Bobby Moynihan]] desperately trying to impress each other on an [[Uber]] ride to boost each other's ratings. The sketch explicitly mentions ''Black Mirror'', with both characters saying that \"San Junipero\" is their favourite episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/recap/saturday-night-live-season-42-episode-12/|title=''Saturday Night Live'' recap: Aziz Ansari|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Holub|first=Christian|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.avclub.com/aziz-ansari-confidently-anchors-a-uniformly-strong-satu-1798190103|title=Aziz Ansari confidently anchors a uniformly strong ''Saturday Night Live''|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Perkins|first=Dennis|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n\"Nosedive\" was mostly well-received by critics. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the episode has a score of 95% based on 20 reviews, with an average score of 7.33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/black_mirror/s03/e01|title=Black Mirror \u2013 Season 3, Episode 1 \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=8 January 2019}}</ref> The episode garnered four-star ratings in ''The Independent'' and ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/black-mirror-season-3-episode-3-s03e03-review-release-date-spoilers-charlie-brooker-netflix-bryce-a7342551.html|title=Black Mirror season 3 episode 1 review: 'A temporary puppeteer of your thoughts'|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|date=3 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian Lee\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/sep/16/black-mirror-first-look-review-charlie-brooker|title=Black Mirror review \u2013 Charlie Brooker's splashy new series is still a sinister marvel|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016|last=Lee|first=Benjamin}}</ref> along with an A\u2212 rating in ''[[The A.V. Club]]''.<ref name=\"avclub\">{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/black-mirror-returns-please-swipe-right-244425|title=''Black Mirror'' returns, please swipe right|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Handlen|first=Zack|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> In ''[[The Mancunion]]'', the episode received 3.5 stars;<ref name=\"mancunion\">{{cite web|url=http://mancunion.com/2016/11/15/review-black-mirror-s3e01-nosedive/|title=Review: Black Mirror S3E01 \u2014 Nosedive|work=[[The Mancunion]]|last=Setranah|first=Emefa|date=15 November 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref> it was rated three stars by ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' and the ''[[Irish Independent]]''.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-season-3-nosedive-review-a-thought-provoking-pastel/|title=Black Mirror, season 3, Nosedive, review: 'a thought-provoking, pastel-coloured hell'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|last=Monahan|first=Mark|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-reviews/black-mirror-is-back-and-its-as-disturbing-as-ever-with-a-few-minor-cracks-35156063.html|title=Black Mirror is back and it's as disturbing as ever... with a few minor cracks|work=[[Irish Independent]]|last=Stacey|first=Pat|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref> Emefa Setranah of ''The Mancunion'' writes that the episode lives up to the show's reputation,<ref name=\"mancunion\"/> and ''The Guardian''{{'s}} Benjamin Lee says the episode feels fresh despite covering technology similarly to prior episodes.<ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/> Charles Bramesco writes in ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'' that it expresses the show's \"guiding theme\" with \"lucid clarity\".<ref name=\"vulture ranking\"/> ''[[TheWrap]]'' authors praise how the episode tackles society's social media obsession,<ref name=\"wrap ranking\"/> and Mat Elfring of [[GameSpot]] opines that its thought-provoking nature makes it a good choice for the season premiere.<ref name=\"gamespot ranking\"/> Matt Fowler writes for [[IGN]] that the episode is \"both fun and frustrating\" which contrasts with the \"grounded and grim\" episodes to follow.<ref name=\"ign\">{{cite web|url=http://ign.com/articles/2016/10/19/black-mirror-season-3-review|title=BLACK MIRROR: SEASON 3 REVIEW|publisher=[[IGN]]|first=Matt|last=Fowler|date=October 19, 2016|accessdate=October 20, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''{{'s}} Corey Atad opines that it is \"a tad too simplistic\" though \"totally engaging\".<ref name=\"esquire ranking\"/> Pat Stacey criticises the episode in the ''Irish Independent'' that it \"sets up the premise crisply, then spends far too much time labouring the point.\"<ref name=\"irish\"/>\n\nA major criticism among reviewers was the episode's predictability and repetitiveness,<ref name=\"mancunion\"/><ref name=\"comingsoon\"/> while reception to the ending was mixed. Aubrey Page on [[Collider (website)|Collider]] calls the episode \"woefully surface-level and a bit off-brand\" because of its predictability,<ref name=\"collider ranking\"/> with ''Variety''{{'s}} Andrew Wallenstein agreeing and further saying that the episode lacks a disturbing tone, though this makes it more accessible.<ref name=\"variety ranking\"/> Zack Handlen of ''The A.V. Club'' believes that the first half of \"Nosedive\" is too predictable but the second half \"[adds] depth and sincerity\".<ref name=\"avclub\"/> Tasha Robinson writes for ''[[The Verge]]'' that the episode \"can be strident and obvious\" but \"understands human nature very well\".<ref name=\"verge\"/> Some reviewers believed the episode was too long and the ending was too positive.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/><ref name=\"avclub\"/><ref name=\"forbes ranking\"/> However, ''[[Digital Spy]]''{{'s}} Alex Mullane praised the ending, because though it is \"bleak in some ways\" it is also \"a moment of sheer, fist-pumping joy\";<ref name=\"ds\"/> Jacob Hall agrees on [[/Film]], calling the ending \"simultaneously cathartic and on-the-nose\".<ref name=\"slash ranking\"/>\n\nHowever, critics had a mostly positive response to the script as a whole, with some noting comedic undertones.<ref name=\"ew ranking\"/> Robinson describes the episode as an \"exaggerated morality play about the dangers of conformity and the small pleasures of individuality\".<ref name=\"verge\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/24/13379204/black-mirror-season-3-episode-1-nosedive-recap|title=Black Mirror's third season opens with a vicious take on social media|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref> The script has been called \"bitingly hilarious\",<ref name=\"collider\"/> \"funny\", \"uplifting\",<ref name=\"ds\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/review/a811645/black-mirror-season-3-review-the-surprise-climax-to-nosedive-is-the-shows-biggest-twist-yet/|title=Black Mirror season 3 'Nosedive' review: this one contains the show's biggest twist yet|work=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Mullane|first=Alex|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref> \"moving\" and \"supremely unsettling\".<ref name=\"vulture ranking\"/> Lee approves of the script avoiding [[exposition (narrative)|exposition]].<ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/> On the other hand, ''The Telegraph''{{'s}} Mark Monahan criticises that the plot and characters do not live up to their potential.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Page feels the episode \"lacks the sadistic snap of Brooker's usual work\".<ref name=\"collider ranking\"/>\n\n[[File:Max Richter - 2015 - ATP Festival.png|thumb|alt=Max Richter performing as a pianist|[[Max Richter]]'s soundtrack for the episode was praised by reviewers.]]\n\nThe episode's visual style and Joe Wright's directing were highly commended;<ref name=\"independent\"/> the setting for the episode garnered positive reception.<ref name=\"collider\"/><ref name=\"Guardian Lee\"/><ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Christian Bone of ''WhatCulture'' praises the \"distinctive pastel-coloured visual palette\"<ref name=\"what ranking\"/> and Hall compliments \"stellar production values\",<ref name=\"slash ranking\"/> while ''Forbes''{{'}} Paul Tassi calls it the \"most visually-stunning\" of the series.<ref name=\"forbes ranking\"/> Sophie Gilbert of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' praises the juxtaposition of calm visuals with narrative tension.<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> Robinson notes that the aesthetics mark a difference between the characters with high and low ratings.<ref name=\"verge\"/> Adam Chitwood comments for Collider that the visual style \"keeps everything focused on the characters\", which is different to Joe Wright's typical style.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/black-mirror-season-3-review-san-junipero-nosedive/|title='Black Mirror' Season 3 Review: \"San Junipero\" and \"Nosedive\" Are a Sunny Start|last=Chitwood|first=Adam|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=15 September 2016|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Setranah notes that Netflix's large budget is apparent in the visuals of the episode,<ref name=\"mancunion\"/> and ''The Independent'' writers suggest it is detailed enough to be revisited.<ref name=\"independent ranking\"/>\n\nMany critics praised Howard's performance,<ref name=\"avclub\"/><ref name=\"mancunion\"/><ref name=\"what ranking\"/> with Atad calling it \"delightfully unhinged\".<ref name=\"esquire ranking\"/> Additionally, Gilbert writes that Howard \"conveys Lacie's inner frustration while grinning cheerfully through it\".<ref name=\"Atlantic\"/> Howard's acting ensures viewers are on Lacie's side, according to Mullane, who also compliments Eve's acting as \"excellent\".<ref name=\"ds\"/>\n\nMax Richter's musical composition for the episode was well-received. ''The Independent'' writers compliment Richter for \"blending the diegetic sounds of the app with the non-diegetic score evoking our protagonist's struggle to determine reality and fiction\",<ref name=\"independent\"/> an element which Robinson also praises.<ref name=\"verge\"/> Fowler calls the score \"very compelling\"<ref name=\"ign\"/> and Monahan describes it as \"elegantly elegiac\".<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\n===Episode ranking===\n\"Nosedive\" appears on many critics' rankings of the 19 episodes in ''Black Mirror'', from best to worst.\n{{col-begin}}{{col-2}}\n* 3rd \u2013 Charles Bramesco, ''[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]''<ref name=\"vulture ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/10/every-black-mirror-episode-from-worst-to-best.html | title=Every Episode of Black Mirror, Ranked From Worst to Best | author=Bramesco, Charles | date=21 October 2016 | website=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]] | publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] | accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 Eric Anthony Glover, ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/every-black-mirror-episode-ranked-worst-best-93082|title=Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked, From Worst to Best|website=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|last=Glover|first=Eric Anthony|date=22 December 2017|accessdate=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801004027/https://www.etonline.com/every-black-mirror-episode-ranked-worst-best-93082|archive-date=2018-08-01|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 5th \u2013 Matt Donnelly and Tim Molloy, ''[[TheWrap]]''<ref name=\"wrap ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thewrap.com/all-13-black-mirror-episodes-ranked-from-good-to-mind-blowing-photos/14/ | title=All 13 'Black Mirror' Episodes Ranked, From Good to Mind-Blowing (Photos) |author1=Donnelly, Matt |author2=Molloy, Tim | website=[[TheWrap]] | accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 5th \u2013 Travis Clark, ''[[Business Insider]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://businessinsider.com/every-black-mirror-episode-on-netflix-ranked-from-worst-to-best-2018-5|title=All 19 episodes of 'Black Mirror,' ranked from worst to best|work=[[Business Insider]]|last=Clark|first=Travis|date=10 September 2018|accessdate=12 September 2018}}</ref>\n* 6th \u2013 Morgan Jeffery, ''[[Digital Spy]]''<ref name=\"ds ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/feature/a780434/black-mirror-episodes-ranked-charlie-brooker/|title=Ranking all 13 episodes of Charlie Brooker's chilling Black Mirror|website=[[Digital Spy]]|last=Jeffery|first=Morgan|date=9 April 2017|accessdate=12 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180806110935/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/black-mirror/feature/a780434/black-mirror-episodes-ranked-charlie-brooker/|archive-date=2018-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n* 8th \u2013 Aubrey Page, ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''<ref name=\"collider ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://collider.com/black-mirror-episodes-ranked | title=Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked From Worst to Best | date=28 October 2016 | author=Page, Aubrey | publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] | accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n* 9th \u2013 James Hibberd, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''<ref name=\"ew ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://ew.com/gallery/black-mirror-episodes-ranked/no-9-nosedive-season-3 | title='Black Mirror': We Rank All 19 Episodes | author=Hibberd, James | date=23 October 2016 | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n* 13th \u2013 Corey Atad, ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''<ref name=\"esquire ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a49919/black-mirror-episodes-ranked/ | title=Every Episode of Black Mirror, Ranked | date=24 October 2016 | author=Atad, Corey | website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] | publisher = [[Hearst Communications]] | accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n* 13th \u2013 Steve Greene, Hanh Nguyen and Liz Shannon Miller, [[IndieWire]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/11/best-black-mirror-episodes-worst-netflix-ranked-1201897973/|title=Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked, From Worst to Best|last1=Greene|first1=Steve|last2=Nguyen|first2=Hanh|last3=Miller|first3=Liz Shannon|publisher=[[IndieWire]]|date=24 November 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\nInstead of by quality, Proma Khosla of [[Mashable]] ranked each episode by tone, concluding that \"Nosedive\" is the 15th most pessimistic of the 19 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/01/05/black-mirror-pessimism-ranking-dread|title=Every 'Black Mirror' episode ever, ranked by overall dread|publisher=[[Mashable]]|last=Khosla|first=Proma|date=5 January 2018|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther critics ranked the 13 episodes in ''Black Mirror''{{'}}s first three series.\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* 3rd \u2013 Christian Bone, ''WhatCulture''<ref name=\"what ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/tv/black-mirror-ranking-every-episode-from-worst-to-best?page=12|title=Black Mirror: Ranking Every Episode From Worst To Best|work=WhatCulture|last=Bone|first=Christian|date=4 November 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 6th \u2013 Adam David, [[CNN Philippines]]<ref name=\"cnn ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/life/entertainment/television/2016/10/24/black-mirror-ranked-episodes.html|title=How to watch all 'Black Mirror' episodes, from worst to best|last=David|first=Adam|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 7th \u2013 Mat Elfring, [[GameSpot]]<ref name=\"gamespot ranking\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/gallery/black-mirror-every-episode-ranked-from-good-to-bes/2900-956/10/ | title=Black Mirror: Every Episode Ranked From Good to Best | author=Elfring, Mat | date=28 October 2016 | publisher=[[GameSpot]] | accessdate=3 February 2017}}</ref>\n* 8th \u2013 Ed Power, ''The Telegraph''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/black-mirror-every-episode-ranked-rated/|title=Black Mirror: every episode ranked and rated|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|last=Power|first=Ed|date=28 December 2017|accessdate=1 January 2018|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n* 9th \u2013 Jacob Hall, [[/Film]]<ref name=\"slash ranking\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/black-mirror-episode-ranking/3/|title=Through a Touchscreen Darkly: Every 'Black Mirror' Episode Ranked|publisher=[[/Film]]|last=Hall|first=Jacob|date=28 October 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 9th (of the Top Ten) \u2013 Brendan Doyle, [[Comingsoon.net]]<ref name=\"comingsoon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/908789-the-top-ten-black-mirror-episodes|title=The Top Ten Black Mirror Episodes|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|last=Doyle|first=Brendan|date=17 December 2017|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 10th \u2013 Andrew Wallenstein, ''Variety''<ref name=\"variety ranking\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/black-mirror-episodes-rank-binge-guide-netflix-1201894706/|title='Black Mirror' Episodes Ranked: Spoiler-Free Guide to Seasons 1\u20133|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Wallenstein|first=Andrew|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\nSome critics ranked the six episodes from series three of ''Black Mirror'' in order of quality.\n* 2nd \u2013 Jacob Stolworthy and Christopher Hooton, ''The Independent''<ref name=\"independent ranking\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/black-mirror-season-3-episodes-1-6-netflix-ranked-a7373321.html|title=Black Mirror review: The season 3 episodes, ranked|work=[[The Independent]]|last1=Stolworthy|first1=Jacob|last2=Hooton|first2=Christopher|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 Paul Tassi, ''[[Forbes]]''<ref name=\"forbes ranking\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2016/10/25/ranking-black-mirror-season-3s-episodes-from-worst-to-best/|title=Ranking 'Black Mirror' Season 3's Episodes From Worst To Best|work=[[Forbes]]|last=Tassi|first=Paul|date=25 October 2016|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 Liam Hoofe, ''Flickering Myth''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2016/10/ranking-black-mirror-season-3-episodes-from-worst-to-best/2/|title=Ranking Black Mirror Season 3 Episodes from Worst to Best|work=Flickering Myth|last=Hoofe|first=Liam|date=29 October 2016|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{{See also|Black Mirror#Accolades}}\n\"Nosedive\" was nominated for several awards in 2017; the third season of ''Black Mirror'' also received several other nominations and awards.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Award nominations for \"Nosedive\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipients\n! Result\n! {{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\n| [[2017 British Academy Television Craft Awards|BAFTA Television Craft Awards]]\n| Best Photography and Lighting \u2013 Fiction\n| [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/television/craft-awards/tv-craft-awards-2017#photography--lighting-fiction---rillington-place|title=Television Craft Awards Winners 2017|publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] (BAFTA)|accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[23rd Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Television Movie or Miniseries]]\n|[[Bryce Dallas Howard]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/2017-sag-awards-nominations-nominees-list-1201941897/|title=SAG Award Nominations: Complete List|publisher=[[SAG-AFTRA|Screen Actors Guild\u2010American Federation of Television and Radio Artists]] (SAG-AFTRA)|first=Seth|last=Kelley|date=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Art Directors Guild Awards 2016|Art Directors Guild Awards]]\n| Excellence in Production Design for a Television Movie or Limited Series\n| Joel Collins, James Foster and Nicholas Palmer <br><small>(Also nominated for \"[[Playtest (Black Mirror)|Playtest]]\" and \"[[San Junipero]]\")</small>\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=Art Directors Guild Awards Nominations: 'Rogue One', 'Game Of Thrones' & More|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/art-directors-guild-nominations-2017-full-list-1201878962/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=5 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[48th NAACP Image Awards|NAACP Image Awards]]\n| Outstanding Writing in a Motion Picture \u2013 Television\n| [[Rashida Jones]] and [[Michael Schur]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2017-naacp-image-award-winners-televised-966471/item/outstanding-literary-work-youth-teens-955892 |title=Hidden Figures, Loving, and Queen of Katwe nominated |last2=Lewis  |first2=Hilary | last1=Washington |first1=Arlene |date=10 February 2017 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=12 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[69th Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Cinematography for a Limited Series or Movie]]\n| [[Seamus McGarvey]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2017/outstanding-cinematography-for-a-miniseries-or-movie|title=69th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Board game==\nBased on the episode, the board game ''Nosedive'' was produced by [[Asmodee]]. Released on 25 November 2018, the game requires between three and six players and is designed to last for roughly 45 minutes.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/15/18097545/black-mirror-nosedive-board-game-asmodee | title = Black Mirror's nightmarish social media episode is now a board game | first = Michael | last = McWhertor | date = 15 November 2018 | accessdate = 1 July 2019 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref> A mobile app, available for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] or [[iOS]], is used to play the game; it initially assigns each player a Social Score. In the initial Lifestyle phase, players draw cards which have ratings between one and five stars, such as the one star card \"A six-minute lunch break\". They tactically assign them to stacks and then each player selects a stack. In the Experience phase, players assign each other experiences such as \"Receiving an anonymous hate cake\" and each player then rates their received experiences from one to five stars. The app then adjusts each player's Social Score based on these ratings. At the end of the game, players earn points from the Lifestyle cards they own which have star ratings less than or equal to their Social Score.<ref name=\"Verge board game\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/12/8/18120393/black-mirror-nosedive-card-app-game-asmodee-review|title=The Black Mirror card game isn't soul-crushing enough to reflect the show|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Robinson|first=Tasha|date=8 December 2018|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nTasha Robinson of ''[[The Verge]]'' criticised the game's mechanics as feeling arbitrary, as users' Social Scores are mostly determined by random factors. However, Robinson praised the app's design, the game's pastel aesthetics and the humour of the Experience cards, which can lead to interesting discussion.<ref name=\"Verge board game\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb episode|5497778|Nosedive}}\n* [http://www.tv.com/shows/black-mirror/nosedive-3425428/ \"Nosedive\"] at [[TV.com]]\n\n{{Black Mirror}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Nosedive (''Black Mirror'')}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nosedive}}\n[[Category:2016 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Augmented reality in fiction]]\n[[Category:Black Mirror episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes about social media]]\n[[Category:Social reputation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Netflix original television series episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Bilorv", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConception and writing:fix Schur image sizing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nosedive_(Black_Mirror)"}
{"title_page": "Pitmiddle", "text_new": "{{infobox UK place \n|static_image_name=\n|static_image_width= \n|static_image_caption= \n|country= Scotland\n|region=\n|unitary_scotland= [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|lieutenancy_scotland = [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = \n|constituency_scottish_parliament1 =  \n|civil_parish=\n|shire_county= \n|official_name= \n|os_grid_reference = \n|coordinates = {{coord|56|27|11|N|3|13|35|W|display=inline}}-\n|map_type = Scotland\n|post_town=PERTH\n|postcode_area= \n|postcode_district=  \n|dial_code=\n|constituency_westminster= }}\n\n'''Pitmiddle''' was a village in the [[Gowrie]] region of [[Perthshire]], Scotland. It is now deserted, the last resident having left in 1938. Its history dates back to the [[12th century]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe earliest form of Pitmiddle's name was ''Petmeodhel'' (''pet'' being a [[Pict]]ish word meaning ''piece of land'', while the origin of ''meodhel'' is unknown).<ref name=psns/>\n\n==Geography==\nLocated {{convert|0.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} north of [[Kinnaird, Gowrie|Kinnaird]] in the centre of the parish, Pitmiddle \"was once a thriving hilltop community and home to several hundred people\",<ref name=courier>''[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]'', 11 April 2020, pp. 22 & 23</ref> but its remote location eventually led to its [[abandoned village|abandonment]].<ref name=courier/> The hills referenced are the Braes of the Carse, which reach heights of around {{convert|180|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns>[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)</ref>\n\nThe location is on a slope overlooking the [[River Tay]], but sheltered from the south by Guardswell Hill and to the north by Pitmiddle Hill, which rises to over {{convert|275|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns/>\n\n==History==\nAlthough Pitmiddle was first called a [[toun]] in 1425,<ref name=psns/> the earliest reference to Pitmiddle is in a charter dating from 1172 to 1174. In it, [[William the Lion]] granted Ralph Rufus \"Kinnaird in its right divisions except ''Petmeodhel'' belonging to Richard my clerk\". This demonstrates that Pitmiddle and Kinnaird were originally [[royal land]]s. Pitmiddle belonged to the [[laird]] of [[Inchture|Inchmartine]]; Kinnaird to the laird of [[Fingask]]. Pitmiddle was held by the Inchmartines for around 150 years. The village itself was never a [[Barony (county division)|barony]], but was likely dealt with as a detached part of the barony of [[Longforgan]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nTenants paid ''cain'' and ''conveth''. Cain was originally a donation to a lord in recognition of his position. Conveth was a hospitality payment made to a lord on his annual visit to his estate. These were originally [[payment]] [[in kind]], in produce from the land.<ref name=psns/> Some tenants may have been [[free tenant|free]], but most were held in some degree of [[serfdom]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe Ogilvy family owned five-sixths of Inchmartine and Pitmiddle in the late [[15th century]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe village was not involved in the [[Jacobite risings]] of 1715 and 1745, but the neighbouring estate of Kinnaird was lost after 1715 due to its owner, Threipland of Fingask, being a supporter of the Jacobite movement.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAgricultural changes in the [[18th century]] affected the nature of the community, eventually leading to its abandonment.<ref name=psns/>\n\nBy 1783, two more touns had been established on land belonging to Pitmiddle, effectively  depriving it of most of its farmland. These were Newtown (now Outfield) to the northeast and Bank (now Guardswell) to the southeast.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAfter the [[Scottish Reformation]], Kinnaird became a separate parish.<ref name=psns/>\n\nToday, hidden amongst farmland and woods, the only remnants of the community are a few crumbling walls and the wild [[redcurrant]] and [[gooseberry]] bushes that once grew in the residents' gardens.<ref name=courier/>\n\n===Settlement and families===\nWilliam Thomassoun was living in Pitmiddle in the 15th century as a \"small but free tenant\". He had a son, Richard.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn 1691, around 250 people lived in the village, along with the hamlet of Craigdallie, which was at the bottom of the hill.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nOn a 1783 map by James Stobie, Pitmiddle appeared as an irregularly shaped cluster of dwellings. The buildings would have been single-storied, made of [[wattle-and-daub]], roofed with turf or thatch \u2013 the latter made from reeds from the banks of the Tay. There would be a single room for living space, with one end cordoned-off for animals. An open hearth would have provided heat, possibly with a hole in the roof to extract smoke. Domestic rubbish would have been thrown onto a [[midden]] near the entrance. Attached to the hut was a yard where hens or pigs foraged and vegetables were grown. Enclosing the settlement was a ditch, beyond which was the arable land, and separated from it by the head [[dyke]] was the pasture.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe main crops grown at Pitmeddle, per three [[17th century|17th-century]] rent rolls, were [[Bere (grain)|bere]] (a four-eared variety of barley) and oats. These also formed the basis of the peasants' diets. [[Wheat]] was later also grown.<ref name=psns/>\n\nPitmiddle is believe to have had a [[shieling]] on Blacklaw (Black Hill) to the north. By 1609, these had been turned into a sheep farm.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the [[16th century]], wright Androu Benbie (possibly Benvie) was living as a [[wright]]. Edmund Jackson was fined ten [[shilling]]s for \"striking the common hird on the [[Sabbath]]\".<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the 17th century, due to a greater survival in documentary evidence, more family names are known. These include: Anderson, Christal, Mores (possibly Morris or Moreis), Morton (possibly Mortoun), Millar, Blair, Mitchell, Whittet, Duncan, Paterson, Ogilvy, Young, Boug, Deucat (possibly Deugatt), Smyth, Christie, Robertson, Matthew, Thom, Gairdner (possibly Gardiner), Bowack (possibly Book, Boug or Boyok), Will, Hall, Muir (possibly Moor or Mure), Pirie (possibly Pierie), Martine and Lawson (possibly Lousone). In 1650, there were 19 tenants.<ref name=psns/>\n\nEarly in the [[19th century]], the homes at Pitmiddle were rebuilt in stone, seemingly on the site of their timber predecessors. They were single storey and thatched. The floors were stone flagged and the fireplaces were built into the gables. The houses were divided into two rooms by box beds. The kitchen fireplace had hooks for kettles and pans. Ashes were kept back by a piece of iron. Around the fireplace was a fender, with a fender stool. The 1861 census showed that all households had two rooms with windows, except John Soutar's farmhouse, which had three. By 1891, there were three families each living in a cottage with three rooms with windows and two families with only one such room, the rest still having two such rooms. Attached to the houses were wooden sheds, [[byre]]s and small gardens. The village's water supply was sourced from three wells.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe rebuilding of the village failed to halt Pitmiddle's demise. A once-thriving community of weavers, a blacksmith, two joiners, a tailor, a butcher and a public house<ref name=scotsman/> was now seeing young people leaving to work in the factories in nearby [[Dundee]] and [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nJust under one hundred people, living in 26 households, made up Pitmiddle's population in 1841.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nIn December 1896, ''[[The Dundee Courier]]'' sent two reporters to Pitmiddle (which had seven families living there at the time) to investigate its living conditions after reports of \"clearance-style\" conditions on the hill. The reporters visited Maidie Mitchell and her sister, \"two very old ladies,\" who had spent their entire lives in Pitmiddle.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nBy 1897, there were only sixteen inhabitants,<ref>Longforgan news article</ref> exactly half of what there were six years earlier.<ref>[https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/perth-kinross/1035486/long-read-soon-there-will-be-nothing-left-the-sad-story-of-taysides-ghost-village/ \"Tayside's lost village\"] - ''The Courier''</ref>\n\nA [[sawmill]] was active from before 1915.<ref>[https://www.forestry-memories.org.uk/picture/number1104/ \"Pitmiddle Sawmill March 1915\"] - Forestry Memories, 11 April 2012</ref> On an [[Ordnance Survey]] map of 1861, a \"mill dam\" is shown southeast of the settlement, towards today's Guardswell Farm.<ref>[https://i0.wp.com/holeousia.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/pitmiddle-village-1861.jpg?ssl=1 Ordnance Survey map, 1861]</ref>\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Inchmartine estate in 1917, Pitmiddle was eventually bought by the White family and farmed from Outfield. In 1930 there were only two houses that were occupied. The final resident, James Gillies Jr., one of ten children  of [[stonemason]] James Sr. (1832\u20131920) and Margaret (1833\u20131908),<ref name=westmuir>[http://www.westmuir.org.uk/PDF%20Pages/Soldiering%20On.pdf \"\u2018Soldiering On\u2019 \u2026\u2026\u2026 and Magdalene\"] - Westmuir.org.uk</ref> left his home there for final time on 4 January, 1938. Winter storms had cancelled the sale of his farm.<ref name=courier/><ref name=psns/><ref name=scotsman>[https://www.scotsman.com/arts-and-culture/when-last-man-left-lost-village-pitmiddle-807807 \"When the last man left the lost village of Pitmiddle\"] - ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 12 September 2018</reF>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)\n*\"The lost village of Pitmiddle\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3g6MDFkv1EA part one], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=979Ff6-nxxs part two] - Jagbetty, [[YouTube]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ms4tdyfuDxw \"Pitmiddle Village Revisited November 2014\"] - wattage2007, YouTube\n*[https://vimeo.com/225400714 \"Pitmiddle - the sun is still shining, long-shadowedly\"] - omphalos, [[Vimeo]]\n*[https://holeousia.com/2017/07/12/pitmiddle-village/ Pitmiddle village] - Hole Ousia\n\n{{Perth & Kinross Towns & Villages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitmiddle}}\n[[Category:Villages in Perth and Kinross]]\n[[Category:Former villages in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox UK place \n|static_image_name=\n|static_image_width= \n|static_image_caption= \n|country= Scotland\n|region=\n|unitary_scotland= [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|lieutenancy_scotland = [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = \n|constituency_scottish_parliament1 =  \n|civil_parish=\n|shire_county= \n|official_name= \n|os_grid_reference = \n|coordinates = {{coord|56|27|11|N|3|13|35|W|display=inline}}-\n|map_type = Scotland\n|post_town=PERTH\n|postcode_area= \n|postcode_district=  \n|dial_code=\n|constituency_westminster= }}\n\n'''Pitmiddle''' was a village in the [[Gowrie]] region of [[Perthshire]], Scotland. It is now deserted, the last resident having left in 1938. Its history dates back to the [[12th century]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe earliest form of Pitmiddle's name was ''Petmeodhel'' (''pet'' being a [[Pict]]ish word meaning ''piece of land'', while the origin of ''meodhel'' is unknown).<ref name=psns/>\n\n==Geography==\nLocated {{convert|0.5|mi|km|abbr=off|0}} north of [[Kinnaird, Gowrie|Kinnaird]] in the centre of the parish, Pitmiddle \"was once a thriving hilltop community and home to several hundred people\",<ref name=courier>''[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]'', 11 April 2020, pp. 22 & 23</ref> but its remote location eventually led to its [[abandoned village|abandonment]].<ref name=courier/> The hills referenced are the Braes of the Carse, which reach heights of around {{convert|180|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns>[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)</ref>\n\nThe location is on a slope overlooking the [[River Tay]], but sheltered from the south by Guardswell Hill and to the north by Pitmiddle Hill, which rises to over {{convert|275|m|ft}}.<ref name=psns/>\n\n==History==\nAlthough Pitmiddle was first called a [[toun]] in 1425,<ref name=psns/> the earliest reference to Pitmiddle is in a charter dating from 1172 to 1174. In it, [[William the Lion]] granted Ralph Rufus \"Kinnaird in its right divisions except ''Petmeodhel'' belonging to Richard my clerk\". This demonstrates that Pitmiddle and Kinnaird were originally [[royal land]]s. Pitmiddle belonged to the [[laird]] of [[Inchture|Inchmartine]]; Kinnaird to the laird of [[Fingask]]. Pitmiddle was held by the Inchmartines for around 150 years. The village itself was never a [[Barony (county division)|barony]], but was likely dealt with as a detached part of the barony of [[Longforgan]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nTenants paid ''cain'' and ''conveth''. Cain was originally a donation to a lord in recognition of his position. Conveth was a hospitality payment made to a lord on his annual visit to his estate. These were originally [[payment]] [[in kind]], in produce from the land.<ref name=psns/> Some tenants may have been [[free tenant|free]], but most were held in some degree of [[serfdom]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe Ogilvy family owned five-sixths of Inchmartine and Pitmiddle in the late [[15th century]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe village was not involved in the [[Jacobite risings]] of 1715 and 1745, but the neighbouring estate of Kinnaird was lost after 1715 due to its owner, Threipland of Fingask, being a supporter of the Jacobite movement.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAgricultural changes in the [[18th century]] affected the nature of the community, eventually leading to its abandonment.<ref name=psns/>\n\nBy 1783, two more touns had been established on land belonging to Pitmiddle, effectively  depriving it of most of its farmland. These were Newtown (now Outfield) to the northeast and Bank (now Guardswell) to the southeast.<ref name=psns/>\n\nAfter the [[Scottish Reformation]], Kinnaird became a separate parish.<ref name=psns/>\n\nToday, hidden amongst farmland and woods, the only remnants of the community are a few crumbling walls and the wild [[redcurrant]] and [[gooseberry]] bushes that once grew in the residents' gardens.<ref name=courier/>\n\n===Settlement and families===\nWilliam Thomassoun was living in Pitmiddle in the 15th century as a \"small but free tenant\". He had a son, Richard.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn 1691, around 250 people lived in the village, along with the hamlet of Craigdallie, which was at the bottom of the hill.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nOn a 1783 map by James Stobie, Pitmiddle appeared as an irregularly shaped cluster of dwellings. The buildings would have been single-storied, made of [[wattle-and-daub]], roofed with turf or thatch \u2013 the latter made from reeds from the banks of the Tay. There would be a single room for living space, with one end cordoned-off for animals. An open hearth would have provided heat, possibly with a hole in the roof to extract smoke. Domestic rubbish would have been thrown onto a [[midden]] near the entrance. Attached to the hut was a yard where hens or pigs foraged and vegetables were grown. Enclosing the settlement was a ditch, beyond which was the arable land, and separated from it by the head [[dyke]] was the pasture.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe main crops grown at Pitmeddle, per three [[17th century|17th-century]] rent rolls, were [[Bere (grain)|bere]] (a four-eared variety of barley) and oats. These also formed the basis of the peasants' diets. [[Wheat]] was later also grown.<ref name=psns/>\n\nPitmiddle is believe to have had a [[shieling]] on Blacklaw (Black Hill) to the north. By 1609, these had been turned into a sheep farm.<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the [[16th century]], wright Androu Benbie (possibly Benvie) was living as a [[wright]]. Edmund Jackson was fined ten [[shilling]]s for \"striking the common hird on the [[Sabbath]]\".<ref name=psns/>\n\nIn the 17th century, due to a greater survival in documentary evidence, more family names are known. These include: Anderson, Christal, Mores (possibly Morris or Moreis), Morton (possibly Mortoun), Millar, Blair, Mitchell, Whittet, Duncan, Paterson, Ogilvy, Young, Boug, Deucat (possibly Deugatt), Smyth, Christie, Robertson, Matthew, Thom, Gairdner (possibly Gardiner), Bowack (possibly Book, Boug or Boyok), Will, Hall, Muir (possibly Moor or Mure), Pirie (possibly Pierie), Martine and Lawson (possibly Lousone). In 1650, there were 19 tenants.<ref name=psns/>\n\nEarly in the [[19th century]], the homes at Pitmiddle were rebuilt in stone, seemingly on the site of their timber predecessors. They were single storey and thatched. The floors were stone flagged and the fireplaces were built into the gables. The houses were divided into two rooms by box beds. The kitchen fireplace had hooks for kettles and pans. Ashes were kept back by a piece of iron. Around the fireplace was a fender, with a fender stool. The 1861 census showed that all households had two rooms with windows, except John Soutar's farmhouse, which had three. By 1891, there were three families each living in a cottage with three rooms with windows and two families with only one such room, the rest still having two such rooms. Attached to the houses were wooden sheds, [[byre]]s and small gardens. The village's water supply was sourced from three wells.<ref name=psns/>\n\nThe rebuilding of the village failed to halt Pitmiddle's demise. A once-thriving community of weavers, a blacksmith, two joiners, a tailor, a butcher and a public house<ref name=scotsman/> was now seeing young people leaving to work in the factories in nearby [[Dundee]] and [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]].<ref name=psns/>\n\nJust under one hundred people, living in 26 households, made up Pitmiddle's population in 1841.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nIn December 1896, ''[[The Dundee Courier]]'' sent two reporters to Pitmiddle (which had seven families living there at the time) to investigate its living conditions after reports of \"clearance-style\" conditions on the hill. The reporters visited Maidie Mitchell and her sister, \"two very old ladies,\" who had spent their entire lives in Pitmiddle.<ref name=scotsman/>\n\nBy 1897, there were only sixteen inhabitants,<ref>Longforgan news article</ref> exactly half of what it was six years earlier.<ref>[https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/perth-kinross/1035486/long-read-soon-there-will-be-nothing-left-the-sad-story-of-taysides-ghost-village/ \"Tayside's lost village\"] - ''The Courier''</ref>\n\nA [[sawmill]] was active from before 1915.<ref>[https://www.forestry-memories.org.uk/picture/number1104/ \"Pitmiddle Sawmill March 1915\"] - Forestry Memories, 11 April 2012</ref> On an [[Ordnance Survey]] map of 1861, a \"mill dam\" is shown southeast of the settlement, towards today's Guardswell Farm.<ref>[https://i0.wp.com/holeousia.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/pitmiddle-village-1861.jpg?ssl=1 Ordnance Survey map, 1861]</ref>\n\nFollowing the breakup of the Inchmartine estate in 1917, Pitmiddle was eventually bought by the White family and farmed from Outfield. In 1930 there were only two houses that were occupied. The final resident, James Gillies Jr., one of ten children  of [[stonemason]] James Sr. (1832\u20131920) and Margaret (1833\u20131908),<ref name=westmuir>[http://www.westmuir.org.uk/PDF%20Pages/Soldiering%20On.pdf \"\u2018Soldiering On\u2019 \u2026\u2026\u2026 and Magdalene\"] - Westmuir.org.uk</ref> left his home there for final time on 4 January, 1938. Winter storms had cancelled the sale of his farm.<ref name=courier/><ref name=psns/><ref name=scotsman>[https://www.scotsman.com/arts-and-culture/when-last-man-left-lost-village-pitmiddle-807807 \"When the last man left the lost village of Pitmiddle\"] - ''[[The Scotsman]]'', 12 September 2018</reF>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.psns.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/PSNS-Pitmiddle-Village-and-Elcho-Nunnery-1988-complete-book.pdf \"Pitmiddle Village and Elcho Nunnery - Research and Excavation on Tayside\"] - Perthshire Society of Natural Science (1988)\n*\"The lost village of Pitmiddle\" [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3g6MDFkv1EA part one], [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=979Ff6-nxxs part two] - Jagbetty, [[YouTube]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ms4tdyfuDxw \"Pitmiddle Village Revisited November 2014\"] - wattage2007, YouTube\n*[https://vimeo.com/225400714 \"Pitmiddle - the sun is still shining, long-shadowedly\"] - omphalos, [[Vimeo]]\n*[https://holeousia.com/2017/07/12/pitmiddle-village/ Pitmiddle village] - Hole Ousia\n\n{{Perth & Kinross Towns & Villages}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pitmiddle}}\n[[Category:Villages in Perth and Kinross]]\n[[Category:Former villages in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSettlement and families", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitmiddle"}
{"title_page": "Marj Al-Ghazal", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Marj Al-Ghazal\n| translit_lang1          = Arabic\n| translit_lang1_type     = [[Arabic script|Arabic]]\n| translit_lang1_info     = \u0645\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0632\u0627\u0644\n| translit_lang1_type1    = [[Latin script|Latin]]\n| translit_lang1_info1    = Marj Al-Ghazal (official)\n| type                    = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Municipality type D (Village council)]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Marj Al-Ghazal within [[State of Palestine|Palestine]]\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| coordinates             = \n| grid_name               = [[Palestine grid|Palestine&nbsp;grid]]\n| grid_position           = \n| subdivision_type        = State\n| subdivision_name        = [[State of Palestine]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Governorates of the Palestinian National Authority|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Jericho Governorate|Jericho]]\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = \n| government_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| government_type         = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Village council]] \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = dunam\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_dunam        = 4917\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_min_m         = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 193\n| population_as_of        = 2007\n| population_note         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Marj Al-Ghazal''' ({{lang-ar|<big>\u0645\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0632\u0627\u0644</big>}}) is a [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] village in the [[Jericho Governorate]] in the [[West Bank]], located  {{convert|34.8|km|mi|sp=us}} north of [[Jericho]].  According to the [[Palestinian Central Bureau of Statistics]] (PCBS), Marj Al-Ghazal had a population of 193 in the 2007 census.\n\n==Location==\nMarj Al-Ghazal is  bordered  by the  [[Jordan River]] to  the  east. Nearby Palestinian localities include [[az-Zubaidat]] to the northeast, [[Al-Jiftlik]] to the south and west.<ref name=\"ARIJ\">[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 4</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the wake of the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], and after the [[1949 Armistice Agreements]], Marj al-Ghazal came under [[Jordan|Jordanian]] rule. It was [[Jordanian annexation of the West Bank|annexed by Jordan]] in 1950.\n\nSince the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967, Marj al-Ghazal has been under [[Israel]]i occupation.\n\nIn 1970, Israel confiscated 509 dunum of village land in order to construct the [[Israeli settlement]] of [[Argaman]].<ref>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 15</ref>\n\nAfter [[Oslo II Accord|1995 accords]], 4% of Marj al-Ghazal\u2019s land was classified as [[Area B]], the remaining 96% as [[Area C (West Bank)|Area C]].<ref>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 14</ref>\n\nIn the 2007 census Marj Al-Ghazal had a population of 193 with exactly 92 being males and 101 females. The total number of households was 43 who lived in 50 housing units.<ref>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 6</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/factsheet/Marj%20al%20Ghazal_FS_EN.pdf Marj al Ghazal Village (Fact Sheet)],  [[Applied Research Institute - Jerusalem]] (ARIJ)\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Marj%20al%20Ghazal_en_Final.pdf Marj al Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/images/english/Marj-al-Ghazal_ap_en.jpg Marj al Ghazal Aerial Photo], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/needsfordevelopment/Marj%20al%20Ghazal_N_EN.pdf Locality Development Priorities and Needs in Marj al Ghazal], ARIJ\n{{Jericho Governorate}}\n\n{{coord missing|Israel}}\n\n[[Category:Jericho Governorate]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Villages in the West Bank]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the State of Palestine]]\n\n\n{{Palestine-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Marj Al-Ghazal\n| translit_lang1          = Arabic\n| translit_lang1_type     = [[Arabic script|Arabic]]\n| translit_lang1_info     = \u0645\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0632\u0627\u0644\n| translit_lang1_type1    = [[Latin script|Latin]]\n| translit_lang1_info1    = Marj Al-Ghazal (official)\n| type                    = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Municipality type D (Village council)]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Marj Al-Ghazal within [[State of Palestine|Palestine]]\n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| coordinates             = \n| grid_name               = [[Palestine grid|Palestine&nbsp;grid]]\n| grid_position           = \n| subdivision_type        = State\n| subdivision_name        = [[State of Palestine]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Governorates of the Palestinian National Authority|Governorate]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Jericho Governorate|Jericho]]\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = \n| government_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| government_type         = [[Village council (Palestinian Authority)|Village council]] \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = dunam\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_dunam        = 4917\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_min_m         = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 193\n| population_as_of        = 2007\n| population_note         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Marj Al-Ghazal''' ({{lang-ar|<big>\u0645\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0632\u0627\u0644</big>}}) is a [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] village in the [[Jericho Governorate]] in the [[West Bank]], located  {{convert|34.8|km|mi|sp=us}} north of [[Jericho]].  According to the [[Palestinian Central Bureau of Statistics]] (PCBS), Marj Al-Ghazal had a population of 193 in the 2007 census.\n\n==Location==\nMarj Al-Ghazal is  bordered  by the  [[Jordan River]] to  the  east. Nearby Palestinian localities include [[az-Zubaidat]] to the northeast, [[Al-Jiftlik]] to the south and west.<ref name=\"ARIJ\">[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 4</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the wake of the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]], and after the [[1949 Armistice Agreements|1-949 Armistice Agreements]], Marj al-Ghazal came under [[Jordan|Jordanian]] rule. It was [[Jordanian annexation of the West Bank|annexed by Jordan]] in 1950.\n\nSince the [[Six-Day War]] in 1967, Marj al-Ghazal has been under [[Israel]]i occupation.\n\nIn 1970, Israel confiscated 509 dunum of village land in order to construct the [[Israeli settlement]] of [[Argaman]].<ref>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 15</ref>\n\nAfter [[Oslo II Accord|1995 accords]], 4% of Marj al-Ghazal\u2019s land was classified as [[Area B]], the remaining 96% as [[Area C (West Bank)|Area C]].<ref>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 14</ref>\n\nIn the 2007 census Marj Al-Ghazal had a population of 193 with exactly 92 being males and 101 females. The total number of households was 43 who lived in 50 housing units.<ref>[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/ar/pdfs/vprofile/marjalghazal.pdf Marj Al-Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ, 2012, p. 6</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/factsheet/Marj%20al%20Ghazal_FS_EN.pdf Marj al Ghazal Village (Fact Sheet)],  [[Applied Research Institute - Jerusalem]] (ARIJ)\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/vprofile/Marj%20al%20Ghazal_en_Final.pdf Marj al Ghazal Village Profile], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/images/english/Marj-al-Ghazal_ap_en.jpg Marj al Ghazal Aerial Photo], ARIJ\n*[http://vprofile.arij.org/jericho/pdfs/needsfordevelopment/Marj%20al%20Ghazal_N_EN.pdf Locality Development Priorities and Needs in Marj al Ghazal], ARIJ\n{{Jericho Governorate}}\n\n{{coord missing|Israel}}\n\n[[Category:Jericho Governorate]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Villages in the West Bank]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the State of Palestine]]\n\n\n{{Palestine-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zarcademan123456", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marj_Al-Ghazal"}
